Interserve. Retrieved 4 April 2013.</ref>\n\n==Corporate social responsibility (CSR)==\n\nInterserve was a constituent of the [[FTSE Group|FTSE]]4Good Index,<ref>[http://shares.telegraph.co.uk/news/article.php?id=954403&archive=1&epic=WMH Markets News] The Daily Telegraph Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> designed to objectively measure the performance of companies that meet globally recognised corporate responsibility standards.<ref>[http://www.ftse.com/Indices/FTSE4Good_Index_Series/index.jsp FTSE4Good Index Series] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204155956/http://ftse.com/Indices/FTSE4Good_Index_Series/index.jsp |date=4 February 2012 }} FTSE Website Retrieved 27 March 2013</ref>\n\n=== CSR history===\n\nThe company has since 2002<ref>[http://www.interserve.com/resources/downloads/investors/report-results/2002-ar-full.pdf Interserve 2002 Annual Report] pages 18-22 Interserve. Retrieved 27 March 2013.</ref> published a [[corporate social responsibility]] report section, as a means of [[social accounting]], within its Annual Report and Financial Results.\n\n''[[The Observer]]''\u2019s \"Good Companies Guide\" 2008, compiled to establish Britain's most ethical companies<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/nov/16/observer-good-companies-guide-1 Ethics still matter in hard times] The Observer 16 November 2008 Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> ranked Interserve in its top 20<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/nov/16/observer-good-companies-guide-2 Top of the class] ''The Observer'', 16 November 2008, Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> out of all companies listed on the [[FTSE 350 Index]]\n\nIn 2012 Interserve established the Interserve Employee Foundation, a [[Charitable organisation|registered charity]],<ref>[http://www.charitycommission.gov.uk/Showcharity/RegisterOfCharities/CharityFramework.aspx?RegisteredCharityNumber=1145338&SubsidiaryNumber=0 Register of Charities] Charity Commission website Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> which as noted in the [[British Quality Foundation]] Achievement Award 2012 citation, \"aims to improve the quality of life and life chances for people in the community where they live and operate by utilising the skills, capabilities, resources and enthusiasm of Interserve's employees.\" <ref>[http://www.bqf.org.uk/awards/achievement/2012-winners BQF Achievement Awards \u2013 2012 Winners] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505214617/http://www.bqf.org.uk/awards/achievement/2012-winners |date=5 May 2014 }} British Quality Foundation website Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref>\n\nIt was announced on 25 March 2013<ref name=csr>[http://www.businessgreen.com/bg/interview/2257016/interserve-reveals-how-it-bridged-the-gap-between-sustainability-and-finance Interserve reveals how it bridged the gap between sustainability and finance] Business Green website 25 March 2013 Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref>\nthat Interserve was to establish an [[Integrated reporting]] accounting system, a series of metrics that are designed to measure more than financial performance,<ref>[http://www.theiirc.org/about/ About IR] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130327115801/http://www.theiirc.org/about/ |date=27 March 2013 }} IIRC website Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> by contributing not only towards financial stability, but also sustainable economic development.<ref>[http://www.theiirc.org/ How IR Will Shape The Future of Reporting] IIRC website Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> The company joined the International Integrated Reporting Council worldwide pilot programme, comprising 85 companies,<ref>[http://www.theiirc.org/companies-and-investors/pilot-programme-business-network/ Pilot Programme Business Network] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130312120912/http://www.theiirc.org/companies-and-investors/pilot-programme-business-network/ |date=12 March 2013 }} IIRC website Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> which sought to develop a reporting system that communicates how an organisation's strategy, governance, performance and prospects lead to the creation of value over the short, medium and long term.\nInterserve developed a plan, \u2018SustainAbilities\u2019,<ref>[http://www.businessgreen.com/bg/news/2256133/interserve-pledges-to-halve-carbon-emissions-by-2020 Interserve pledges to halve carbon emissions by 2020] Business Green website 21 March 2013 Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> in conjunction with sustainability adviser, environmentalist and writer [[Tony Juniper]],<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/tonyjuniper Tony Juniper profile] The Guardian Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> co-founder of The Robertsbridge Group,<ref name=csr/> that would measure the company's performance against its knowledge, natural and social capital, in addition to its financial capital.\n\n===Accreditations===\n\nInterserve is accredited with compliance to the following [[International Organization for Standardization]] (ISO) standards:<ref>[http://www.interserve.com/resources/microsites/downloads/sustainability/Sustainability_report_2010.pdf Company Sustainability report 2010] Company website Retrieved 2 April 2013</ref>\n* [[ISO 9000|ISO 9001]] - [[Quality Management]] - deals with the requirements that organisations have to comply with<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iso.org/iso/iso_9000_selection_and_use.htm|title=ISO 9000 selection and use|publisher=International Standards Organisation}}</ref> to meet the fundamentals of quality management systems,<ref name=\"Tsim, Yeung, Leung 2002\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1108/02686900210429669 |title=An adaptation to ISO 9001:2000 for certified organisations |year=2002 |last1=Tsim |first1=Y.C. |last2=Yeung |first2=V.W.S. |last3=Leung |first3=Edgar T.C. |journal=Managerial Auditing Journal |volume=17 |issue=5 |page=245}}</ref> including the eight management principles<ref name=\"Tsim, Yeung, Leung 2002\"/><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/0954412998090 |title=Implementing ISO 9000: A study of its benefits among Australian organizations |year=1999 |last1=Beattie |first1=Ken R. |journal=Total Quality Management |volume=10 |page=95}}</ref> on which the family of standards is based.\n*[[ISO 14000|ISO 14001]] - [[Environmental Management]] - is a standard that sets out the criteria that organisations processes are required to achieve in order to; (a) minimize how their operations (processes etc.) negatively affect the environment (i.e. cause adverse changes to air, water, or land); (b) comply with applicable laws, regulations, and other environmentally oriented requirements, and (c) continually improve in the above.\n* [[OHSAS 18001]] -  [[Occupational Health and Safety]] (OH&S) -  is an international standard for occupational health and  safety [[management system]]s. It specifies the requirements for an organisations OH&S management system that documents through a transparent process its policy and objectives, to take into account legal requirements and information about OH&S risks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bsigroup.com/en/Assessment-and-certification-services/management-systems/Standards-and-Schemes/BSOHSAS-18001/|title=BS OHSAS 18001 Occupational Health and Safety - BSI Group|work=bsigroup.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://opim.wharton.upenn.edu/risk/library/J2007_ESUvol17_PJS.pdf Gamecocks fly safer with OHSAS 18001, QUALITY SYSTEMS UPDATE Volume 17, Number 4, Page 13, 2007<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n\nInterserve have been recipients of the following business and industry awards:\n\n* [[Royal Society for the Prevention of Accidents]] ([[RoSPA]]) \u2013 President's Award <ref name=\"rospa1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2012/presidents-award.aspx|title=President's Award|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n* Interserve Construction 2012,<ref name=\"rospa1\"/> 2011,<ref name=\"rospa2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2011/presidents-award.aspx|title=Winners|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2010/presidents-award.aspx|title=Winners|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n* Interserve Engineering Services 2012,<ref name=\"rospa1\"/> 2011,<ref name=\"rospa2\"/>\n* Interserve Defence 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2009/presidents-award.aspx|title=Winners|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2008/presidents-award.aspx|title=Winners|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2007/presidents-award.aspx|title=Winners|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2006/presidents-award.aspx|title=Winners|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n* Interserve Industrial Services 2005,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2005/presidents-award.aspx|title=Winners|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2004/presidents-award.aspx|title=Winners|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n* British Quality Foundation UK Excellence Award 2012 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bqf.org.uk/awards/ukea/2012-winners|title=UK Excellence Award - 2012 Winners|work=bqf.org.uk|accessdate=22 March 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130423185111/http://www.bqf.org.uk/awards/ukea/2012-winners|archive-date=23 April 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> - Interserve Construction\n* The [[Queen's Award for Enterprise]] 2010<ref>[http://www.birminghampost.net/birmingham-business/birmingham-business-news/business-entrepreneurship/2010/04/30/west-midlands-successes-in-the-queen-s-awards-for-enterprise-65233-26351990/ West Midlands successes in the Queen's Awards for Enterprise] Birmingham Post 30 April 2010</ref> - RMD Kwikform\n* The [[British Safety Council]] \u2013 International Safety Award 2013 \u2013 Distinction \u2013 Interserve Industrial Services Limited<ref>[https://www.britsafe.org/sites/default/files//editor/2013%20ISA%20winners%20list.pdf British Safety Council International Safety Award Winners 2013] British Safety Council website Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref>\n\n==Corporate lobbying==\n\nInterserve has been a member of [[Constructing Excellence]],<ref>[http://www.constructingexcellence.org.uk/membership/memberlist.jsp Constructing Excellence Membership List] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20130423193416/http://www.constructingexcellence.org.uk/membership/memberlist.jsp |date=23 April 2013 }} Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> The [[Business Services Association]]<ref>[http://www.bsa-org.com/about/members The Business Service Association Membership List] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> and [[Build UK]].<ref>[http://builduk.org/members/ Build UK contractor members] Retrieved 1 September 2015</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Accounting irregularities===\n\nOn 14 August 2006 the company announced to the London Stock Exchange that accounting issues relating to the mis-statement of accounting balances within its former Industrial Services Division had been uncovered.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fildes |first=Nic |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/interserve-shares-dive-after-staff-are-suspended-over-fraud-claim-411975.html |title=Interserve shares dive after staff are suspended over fraud claim |publisher=The Independent |date=2006-08-15 |accessdate=2019-03-01}}</ref> The discovery of these accounting irregularities led to a write down in profits by \u00a325.9m, including prior years (see section 3 Financial Information), and six senior managers were suspended with the company stating that accounting mis-statements dating back \"several years\" had been uncovered following changes in the organisation. The ''Daily Telegraph'' reported that 'an investigation had discovered that controls in the division involving work in progress were, in the words of Lord Blackwell, chairman, \"repeatedly evaded over several years in what appears to have been a concerted effort by certain divisional managers to over-state divisional results.\" He added that the board was concerned that the deliberate nature of the evasions had gone undetected for so long despite internal and external audit scrutiny.'<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/2948088/Interserve-finds-accounting-irregularities.html Interserve finds accounting irregularities] The Daily Telegraph 28 September 2006 Retrieved 11 March 2013</ref>\n\n===Office of Fair Trading investigation===\n\nIt was announced that in April 2008 the company became subject to an investigation by the [[Office of Fair Trading]] ([[Office of Fair Trading|OFT]]) under the terms of the Competition Act.<ref>[http://www.oft.gov.uk/news-and-updates/press/2008/52-08#.UTPdGxy4knR OFT issues statement of objections against 112 construction companies] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130311001325/http://oft.gov.uk/news-and-updates/press/2008/52-08#.UTPdGxy4knR |date=11 March 2013 }} Office of Fair Trading Press Release 17 April 2008</ref> The investigation was described by the OFT as \"one of the largest ever Competition Act investigations\" and a total of 112 firms in the construction sector in England were implicated. On 22 September 2009 the OFT concluded that Interserve subsidiary Interserve Project Services Limited had engaged in illegal anti-competitive bid-rigging activities<ref>[http://www.oft.gov.uk/news-and-updates/press/2009/114-09#.UTPd3xy4knT Construction firms fined for illegal bid-rigging] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130310070444/http://oft.gov.uk/news-and-updates/press/2009/114-09#.UTPd3xy4knT |date=10 March 2013 }} Office of Fair Trading Press Release 22 September 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/e1ea26ee-a741-11de-9467-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2MVzHknm5 Builders fined \u00a3130M for rigging bids] Financial Times 22 September 2009</ref> and imposed a fine of \u00a311,634,750.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/business_leaflets/general/parties2.pdf |title=Office of Fair Trading Press Release |access-date=3 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018054827/http://oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/business_leaflets/general/parties2.pdf |archive-date=18 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Alleged blacklisting===\n\nA case was brought by three claimants who were scaffolders and [[Union representative|shop stewards]], against subsidiary company Interserve Industrial Services Limited (IIS) at an [[Employment Tribunal]].<ref name=et1>[http://www.lexology.com/library/detail.aspx?g=9f6d02de-9f63-4805-9447-1057d77ba297 Employer not liable in union blacklisting case] Lexology website 12 December 2012 Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> IIS and the claimants [[trade union]], [[UNITE]], were party to a [[collective agreement]] that provided for the company to \"undertake as far as is practicable to place onto an appropriate contract an NECC accredited senior steward\". A union representative therefore contacted a manager for the company and advocated the employment of the claimants on a contract awarded to IIS. The manager decided on the basis of the contact with the union representative not to recruit any of the three claimants.<ref name=et2>[http://www.employmentcasesupdate.co.uk/site.aspx?i=ed14300 Miller & Ors v Interserve Industrial Services Ltd UKEAT/0244/12/SM] Employment Case Update website Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> The claimants contended that a deliberate decision had been made not to recruit them because of their union activities and that their names had been blacklisted by the company.<ref name=et3>[http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2012/12/11/interserve-beats-blacklist-charge-by-scaffolders/ Interserve beats blacklist charge by scaffolders] Construction Enquirer website Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> The Tribunal ruling supported the IIS evidence that the union tried to bully the company's manager into employing the three men, acted in a combative manner which was resented and that the company did not want to be dictated to about whom to employ.<ref name=et4>[http://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/interserve-cleared-of-blacklisting-allegation Interserve Cleared of blacklisting allegation] The Construction Index website 11 December 2012 Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> The judgement was subject to an [[Employment Appeal Tribunal]] where the ruling was upheld in Interserve's favour.<ref name=et1/><ref name=et2/><ref name=et3/><ref name=et4/>\n\n===Late payment===\nIn April 2019, Interserve Construction was suspended from the UK Government's [[Prompt payment|Prompt Payment Code]] for failing to pay suppliers on time.<ref name=\"Morby-29Apr2019\">{{cite news |last1=Morby |first1=Aaron |title=Industry giants shamed over late payment |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2019/04/29/industry-giants-shamed-over-late-payment/ |accessdate=29 April 2019 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=29 April 2019}}</ref> It was reinstated in November 2019.<ref name=\"TCI-4Nov2019\">{{cite news |title=Late-paying Kier suspended from Prompt Payment Code |url=https://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/late-paying-kier-suspended-from-prompt-payment-code |accessdate=4 November 2019 |work=The Construction Index |date=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notable construction projects==\n*[[Westminster Bridge]] refurbishment, described by [[Transport for London]] (TFL) as \"revolutionary works to repair the Capital's oldest bridge\"; constructed by Interserve Project Services.<ref>[http://www.tfl.gov.uk/static/corporate/media/newscentre/archive/6246.html Westminster Bridge scoops engineering award] Transport for London website 19 October 2007 Retrieved 11 March 2013</ref>\n*[[Thames Water Desalination Plant]], The first [[water desalination]] plant in the United Kingdom, built in [[Beckton]], east London for [[Thames Water]] by a consortium of Interserve, [[Atkins (company)|Atkins Water]] and Spanish firm [[Acciona]] Agua<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120425235259/http://www.building.co.uk/news/interserve-group-to-build-%C2%A3200m-thames-gateway-water-scheme/3117836.article Interserve group to build \u00a3200m Thames Gateway water scheme] Building Magazine 9 July 2009 Retrieved 2 April 2013</ref>\n\n===Constructed as Tilbury Douglas===\n*[[London Eye]], the Eye is described by its operators as \"the world's tallest [[cantilever]]ed [[observation wheel]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londoneye.com/AboutUs/MerlinEntertainmentGroup/Default.aspx|title=Merlin Entertainments Group|author=Graphico|work=The London Eye|accessdate=22 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329084502/https://www.londoneye.com/AboutUs/MerlinEntertainmentGroup/Default.aspx|archive-date=29 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ingenia.org.uk/ingenia/articles.aspx?Index=77 The Wheel: The British Airways London Eye] Ingenia Issue 6, November 2000, the online journal published by The Royal Academy of Engineering. London</ref><ref>[https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/archive/eye-eye-3-10-06-1999/ Eye Eye] Construction News 10 June 1999 Retrieved 11 March 2013</ref>\n*[[Murrayfield Stadium]], [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]], home of the [[Scottish Rugby Union]] and home venue for [[Scotland national rugby union team|the Scottish National Rugby team]], as well as hosting games in the [[1991 Rugby World Cup|1991]], [[1999 Rugby World Cup|1999]] and [[2007 Rugby World Cup]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/archive/18feb93-uk-tilbury-scores-try-20m-stadium-redevelopment-cntract-18-02-1993/|title=18Feb93 UK: TILBURY SCORES TRY - \u00a320M STADIUM REDEVELOPMENT CONTRACT.|work=https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n*[[The Den]], [[Bermondsey]], southeast London home of English [[Association Football|football]] club [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/archive/25mar93-uk-lions-new-den-millwall-fc-25-03-1993/|title=25Mar93 UK: LIONS' NEW DEN - MILLWALL FC.|work=https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Rothera Research Station]], [[Adelaide Island]], [[British Antarctic Territory]] for [[British Antarctic Survey]].<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Jxq-t-yLFmcC&pg=PT147&lpg=PT147&dq=tilbury+douglas+construction+contracts|title=A Summer in Antarctica |year=2011 |author1=  Jones, J.J. |accessdate=11 March 2013 |isbn=978-1467880077 |publisher=Author House |location = UK}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=mO6gV1BUB7MC&pg=PT104&lpg=PT104&dq=british+antarctic+survey+tilbury+douglas|title= Terra Incognita: Travels in Antarctica |year=2010 |author1=  Wheeler, Sara. |accessdate=11 March 2013 |isbn=978-1407051826 |publisher=Random House |location =London, UK}}</ref><ref>[https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/archive/01apr93-antarctica-builders-feel-chill-of-rising-costs-research-station-01-04-1993/ Antarctica: Builders Feel Chill of Rising Costs \u2013 Research Station] Construction News 1 April 1993 Retrieved 11 March 2013</ref>\n\n===Constructed by RM Douglas===\n*[[International Convention Centre, Birmingham]], constructed in joint venture with Turner International.<ref name=\"thefreelibrary.com\">[http://www.thefreelibrary.com/High+regard+for+council+in+skyline+awards.-a069962270 High Regard for council in skyline awards] The Birmingham Post 3 February 2001 Retrieved 11 March 2013</ref><ref>[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/0100news/0100localnews/tm_objectid=15130532&method=full&siteid=50002&headline=man-who-helped-build-new-brum-name_page.html Man who helped build new Brum] The Birmingham Post 29 January 2005 Retrieved 11 March 2013</ref>\n*[[Symphony Hall, Birmingham]], home of the [[City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra]] (part of the International Convention Centre project).\n*[[National Exhibition Centre]], Birmingham, UK.<ref name=\"thefreelibrary.com\"/><ref>[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/0100news/0100localnews/tm_objectid=15130532&method=full&siteid=50002&headline=man-who-helped-build-new-brum-name_page.html Man who helped build new Brum] The Birmingham Post 3 February 2001 Retrieved 29 January 2005</ref>\n*[[Don Valley Stadium]], [[Sheffield]], [[England]], venue for the 1991 [[Universiade|World Student Games]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.supertram.com/donvalley.html|title=Stagecoach Supertram: The Don Valley|work=supertram.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Controlled-access highway|Motorways]] including:\n** [[M1 motorway|M1]]<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m1/m1-crick-to-barlborough-j18-to-j30/index.cfm The Motorway Archive] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> - Jct 18 to 30 (Kirby Muxloe \u2013 Whetstone) and Jct 18 to 30 (Nuthall \u2013 Sandiacre)\n** [[M4 motorway|M4]]<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m4/m4-wales/m4-in-wales-contract-details.cfm The Motorway Archive] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> - East of Jct37(A48) to Jct39 (Pyle by-pass) and J44 to J46 (Morriston by-pass)<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m4/m4-wales/m4-in-wales-lon-las-to-llangyfelach-j44-to-j46. The Motorway Archive] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041233/http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m4/m4-wales/m4-in-wales-lon-las-to-llangyfelach-j44-to-j46. |date=4 March 2016 }} Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref>\n** [[M40 motorway|M40]]<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m40/m40-waterstock-j8a-to-umberslade-m42--j3a/index.cfm The Motorway Archive] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> - Jct13 to Jct15 (Warwick South) and Jct12 to Jct13 (Gaydon)\n** [[M42 motorway|M42]]<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m42-birmingham-to-nottingham-motorway-M5-j4a-to-tamworth-j11/lickey-end-j1-to-alvechurch-j2.cfm The Motorway Archive] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> - Jct1 to Jct2 (Lickey End to Alvechurch) and Jct4 to Jct8 (Solihull Section)<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m42-birmingham-to-nottingham-motorway-m5-j4a-to-tamworth-j11/solihull-section-j4-to-j8 The Motorway Archive] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> \n** [[M50 motorway (Great Britain)|M50]]<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m50-the-ross-spur-motorway--ross-bypass/index.cfm The Motorway Archive] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref>\n** [[M54 motorway|M54]]<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m54-the-telford-motorway/index.cfm The Motorway Archive] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> - Jct1 to Jct3 (Donington section)\n** [[M6 motorway|M6]]<ref name=m6>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m5/m5-j1-to-j3-and-m6-j13-to-j1-midland-links-motorways/index. The Motorway Archive] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304043724/http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m5/m5-j1-to-j3-and-m6-j13-to-j1-midland-links-motorways/index. |date=4 March 2016 }} Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> - Jct7 to Jct8 (Rayhall to Great Barr), North of Jct6 to Jct7 (Great Barr to Perry Bar) and advance river works for [[Gravelly Hill Interchange]] colloquially known as [[Spaghetti Junction]]\n** [[A38(M)]]<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/midlands.htm The Motorway Archive] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> - Tower Road to Inner Ring Road (Lancaster Circus).\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Lightering|Lighterage]] \n* [[Facilities management]]\n* [[Dredging]]\n* [[Dunkirk evacuation]]\n* [[Confederation of British Industry]]\n* [[RMD Kwikform]]\n* [[Office of Fair Trading]]\n* [[Integrated reporting]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.interserve.com/default.asp Official site]\n* [http://uk.finance.yahoo.com/q/pr?s=IRV.L Yahoo profile]\n* [http://markets.ft.com/Research/Markets/Tearsheets/Summary?s=IRV:LSE FT.com tearsheet]\n\n{{Construction industry in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Construction and civil engineering companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Business services companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the London Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Construction and civil engineering companies established in 1884]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Reading, Berkshire]]\n[[Category:Private providers of NHS services]]\n[[Category:Business services companies established in 1884]]\n[[Category:1884 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Christian mission agency Interserve|International Service Fellowship}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox company \n| name = Interserve Group Ltd\n| logo = Interserve logo.svg\n|type= [[Limited company]]\n|traded_as= \n| industry = Infrastructure - professional services, construction services, support services, construction equipment hire and sale\n|predecessor= Interserve plc<br/>Tilbury Douglas plc<br/>Tilbury Group plc<br/>R M Douglas Holdings\n| foundation = 1884\n|location_city= [[Reading, Berkshire]]\n |area_served= Worldwide\n| key_people = [[Alan Lovell]], [[Chair (official)|Chairman]]\n| products = [[Formwork|Formwork Systems]], Joinery products\n| revenue = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]2,697.5 million (2018)<ref name=\"2018Results\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rns-pdf.londonstockexchange.com/rns/2591R_1-2019-2-27.pdf|title=Interserve PLC Full Year Results Announcement 2018|publisher=Interserve|date=27 February 2019 |accessdate=27 February 2019 }}</ref>\n| operating_income = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]75.4 million (2018)<ref name=\"2018Results\"/>\n| net_income = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]](128.9) million (2018)<ref name=\"2018Results\"/>\n| num_employees = 60,500 (2019)<ref name=\"about-us\">{{cite web|url=https://www.interserve.com/about-us|title=About us|publisher=Interserve|accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref>\n| parent = \n| subsid = see [[#Operations|Operations]]\n| footnotes =\n|location_country= [[United Kingdom]]\n | homepage = [http://www.interserve.com www.interserve.com]\n}}\n\n'''Interserve''' is a [[multinational corporation|multinational]] group of support services and [[construction]] companies based in the [[United Kingdom|UK]], with a [[revenue]] of \u00a32.7 billion in 2018 and a [[workforce]] of 68,000 people worldwide.<ref name=\"2018Results\"/> The group has its [[headquarters]] in [[Reading, Berkshire]].\n\nThe company was founded in 1884 as the '''London and Tilbury Lighterage Company Limited''', and retained the Tilbury name until 2001. From 1991 it was known as '''Tilbury Douglas''' following a merger with RM Douglas, but in 2001 rebranded as '''Interserve plc'''. The name change partly reflected a shift in focus during the 1990s towards [[Property maintenance|maintenance]] and [[facilities management]] services sectors, and this continued in the 2000s, buoyed by further acquisitions.\n\nHowever, financial issues including problem contracts in Interserve's [[energy-from-waste]] business led to profit warnings in 2017. The company was forced to restructure and refinance in March 2018. Its financial situation worsened in late 2018, and debt holders started discussing a further financial restructuring of the business. The debt-for-equity plan was rejected at an [[annual general meeting]] on 15 March 2019, and the parent company went into [[administration (law)|administration]] owing creditors over \u00a3100m. In a [[Pre-packaged insolvency|pre-pack deal]], the rest of the group was immediately sold to a newly incorporated company owned by lenders, '''Interserve Group Ltd''', with a break-up of the company expected in 2020.\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history \u2013 1884 to 1930s===\n\n====Origins====\nInterserve traces its origins to 1884, when the '''London and Tilbury Lighterage Company Limited''' was formed to transfer [[good (economics)|goods]] by [[sailing barge]] to and from [[ships]] on the [[River Thames]], [[London]], [[England]].<ref name=history>[http://www.interserve.com/about-interserve/our-history Interserve History] Company website Retrieved 11 March 2013</ref> A [[Lightering|lighterage]] is the fee paid for the use of a [[lighter (barge)|lighter]],<ref>[http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/lighterage Dictionary.com] Definition of Lighterage</ref> a large, open, flat bottomed barge, that could transport goods a short distance in shallow waters.<ref>[http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/lighter Dictionary.com] Definition of Lighter</ref> At the time London was the busiest [[port]] in the [[world]].<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=nYh5KtDGt7IC&pg=PT16&lpg=PT16&dq=the+busiest+port+in+the+world+1880 |title=City Of Cities: The Birth Of Modern London |year=2011 |author1=  Inwood, Stephen. |accessdate=13 March 2013 |isbn=978-0330540674 |publisher=Pan Macmillan |location =London, UK}}</ref> Lightering provided a service  much in demand in the overcrowded river because of the need to transship goods from ships berthed there and to convey them to the riverside [[wharf|wharves]], where the larger open water [[cargo ship]]s were unable to dock due to their size and [[Draft (hull)|draft]] or, to more efficiently and effectively deal with the number of ships congregating in the river.<ref>[http://www.lighteragetugs.co.uk/ London Lighterage Tugs] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130327143350/http://www.lighteragetugs.co.uk/ |date=27 March 2013 }} London Lighterage Tugs website Retrieved 13 March 2013</ref> By 1887 the company is recorded as occupying premises of a former [[Lloyd's Register]] Proving House and Chain-Testing Shed and subsequent Police Station at Preston Road, [[West India Docks]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=46541&strquery=tilbury+lighterage |title=Southern Blackwall: Preston's Road area |author=Hermione Hobhouse (General Editor) |publisher=Institute of Historical Research |year=1994 |work=Survey of London: volumes 43 and 44: Poplar, Blackwall and Isle of Dogs |accessdate=18 March 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1888 the company expanded into [[dredging]], where mechanisation led to greatly improved [[productivity]], and secured a [[contract]] with the [[Port of London]] (PLA) to remove dredged ballast.<ref name=history/> This new venture was complementary to the existing business,  utilising the barges already owned by the company, together with their knowledge of the river and its tides. There was a further synergy between lightering and dredging; lightering was necessary where ports were shallow and the draft of a vessel needed to be reduced to facilitate their entry into [[port]], whereas dredging increased the depth of river channels to enable vessels with a larger draft to [[Berth (moorings)|berth]] into port. The company's move into dredging therefore protected its commercial interest against the perceived threat to lightering. This can be seen vindicated by the decline in lighterage for dry [[bulk cargo]] after the middle of the 20th century, although the eventual decline in lighterage was caused by the adoption of [[road haulage]] as the main distribution method when London's docks moved downstream (away from what is now known as [[London Docklands|Docklands]]) and [[shipping]] adopted [[containerisation]] methods.<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1967/dec/18/thames-lighterage-industry UK Parliamentary Debate 18 December 1967] Hansard 18 December 1967 Retrieved 18 March 2013</ref> However, for the time being lightering still thrived and the [[New Zealand]]-based ''[[Ashburton Guardian]]'' reported in 1890 that the company was an early pioneer in the transshipment of frozen meat. The newspaper noted that their capabilities for handling this cargo had been highlighted during a trip, organized for delegates at the International Congress on Inland Navigation, to inspect the company's custom built vessels complete with cold chambers that enabled the meat to arrive at [[Smithfield Market]] frozen.<ref>[http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=AG18900925.2.5&dliv=&e=-------10--1----0-- Frozen Meat for London] Ashburton Guardian 25 September 1890 Retrieved from Papers Past 18 March 2013</ref>\n\n====Name changes and international presence====\nThe company changed its name several times over the next few years; in 1896 to '''The London and Tilbury Lighterage Contracting and Dredging Company Limited''', in 1904 to the '''Tilbury Contracting and Dredging Company Limited''', then in 1906 to '''Tilbury Contracting and Dredging Company (1906) Limited''', before In 1908 reverting to '''Tilbury Contracting and Dredging Company Limited''' (TCDC), a name it settled on for the following 56 years.<ref name=history/> These were not the only changes experienced by the business, for the advance of technology meant that the firm's sailing barges were becoming obsolete by the advent of steam [[tugs]], and the Company commissioned the new tugs to be built.<ref name=thamestugs>[http://www.thamestugs.co.uk/T--C---and--D--LTD.php Tilbury Contracting and Dredging Company Limited] Thames Tugs History Website Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> As the company grew, so did its profile and it came to be frequently featured in the pages of ''[[The Engineer (UK magazine)|The Engineer]]''. Mention is made in 1907 of the role played by its dredging craft in widening and deepening the navigation channel of the [[River Clyde]] to assist the maiden voyage of [[RMS Lusitania]], then the world's biggest ship.<ref name=theengineer>{{cite journal|title=Cunard Turbine Liner Luisitania|journal=The Engineer|date=5 July 1907|page=10|url= http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/images/9/9a/Er19070705b.pdf|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref> A further example was reported on 9 June 1911<ref>{{cite journal|title=Improvement of the Port of Nantes|journal=The Engineer|date=9 June 1911|page=588|url=http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/images/e/ee/Er19110609.pdf|accessdate=20 March 2013}}</ref> which in an article about major dredging works to the [[River Loire]] around the port of [[Nantes]], [[France]], noted that the company \"had a special dredger constructed for the purpose\". This contract is noteworthy as it comprised, at commencement, a three-year undertaking to form a new river bed to divert the course of the river, as well as removing islands and sand banks. A total of 10 million cubic metres of material was to be dredged as part of these \u00a31&nbsp;million<ref name=theengineer/> (2013 = \u00a392.5&nbsp;million<ref>[http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/bills/article-1633409/Historic-inflation-calculator-value-money-changed-1900.html Historic inflation calculator: how the value of money has changed since 1900 Historic inflation calculator: how the value of money has changed since 1900] Daily Mail Retrieved 20 March 2013</ref>) works. On 9 December 1911 [[Singaporean]] newspaper ''The Weekly Sun'' reported that TCDC \"the well-known dredging contractors of London, have entered into a contract\u2026for the formation of a port known as Port Argentine\" involving the dredging of 16 million cubic metres to form an approach channel some 9.5 miles long in the [[Buenos Aires]] province.<ref>[http://newspapers.nl.sg/Digitised/Article/weeklysun19111209.2.39.aspx A Big Dredging Contract] The Weekly Sun Singapore 9 December 1911 Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> During this period the company also carried out dredging projects in [[Canada]], [[Egypt]] and [[Denmark]].<ref>[http://lewishamwarmemorials.wikidot.com/person:hughes-frederick-peter Obituary \u2013 Lieutenant Frederick Peter Hughes, MC] The Times 16 August 1918 Retrieved from Lewisham War Memorials website 28 March 2013</ref>\n\n====World War I service====\nA number of the company's [[marine vessel|vessels]] were [[Eminent domain|requisitioned]] for [[war]] duties during [[World War I]] where they took part in various [[military campaign]]s including in the [[Dardanelles]], [[Archangel]] and the [[Persian Gulf]].<ref name=thamestugs/> Company tug 'Danube' was transferred to [[Admiralty]] control and assisted a [[Monitor (warship)|monitor]] through the [[Mediterranean]] en route to the [[Rufiji River]] [[River delta|delta]], in present-day [[Tanzania]], in order to destroy the German raider [[SMS K\u00f6nigsberg (1915)|Konigsberg]].<ref name=thamestugs/>\n\n====Exit from lighterage====\nLightering gradually declined due to the increase of [[road traffic]], and dredging became the mainstay of the company.<ref name=profile>[http://listofcompanies.co.in/interserve-plc/ List of Companies company profile] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> In addition to its dredging contract with the PLA, TCDC secured many other contracts including, between 1923 and 1927, the deepening and on going maintenance of the depth of the [[Channel (geography)|navigation channel]] and [[Harbor|tidal harbour]] at the Port of [[Aberdeen]] <ref>[http://www.pla.co.uk/pdfs/PLA_Monthly_1929.pdf Company Advert]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} P.L.A Monthly The Magazine of The Port of London Authority April 1929 Retrieved 20 March 2013</ref> 1932 saw the firm begin work on a new harbour at Haifa in British Mandate Territory of Palestine that was completed in 1934.<ref>[http://www.charlesglass.net/archives/2007/05/obituary_major.html Obituary - Major Derek Cooper, MC, OBE, World War II hero who espoused the Palestinian cause] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150621064634/http://www.charlesglass.net/archives/2007/05/obituary_major.html |date=21 June 2015 }} The Independent 31 May 2007 Retrieved from Charles Glass website 28 March 2013</ref> In 1938 the company's lighterage fleet was amalgamated with vessels owned by W H J Alexander Limited and [[Tate and Lyle]] Limited to form Silvertown Services Limited<ref name=thamestugs/> and TCDC severed its links with its original business activity.<ref name=history/>\n\n===World War II service \u2013 1940 to 1945===\nAs in World War I, many of the company's fleet of tugs were requisitioned for active service during [[World War II]]. These initially came under the control of the [[Royal Navy]] examination service,<ref name=thamestugs/> where they were used to patrol harbour and river entrances. The role of the examination service crews was to board all merchant ships and trawlers entering ports or rivers, scrutinise their papers and if need be to search these craft for evidence of intent to help the enemy.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ww2peopleswar/stories/60/a4179260.shtml BBC WW2 People's War - An Archive of World War Two Memories] BBC History Website 11 June 2005 Retrieved 17 March 2013</ref>\n\n====Operation Dynamo====\nAlthough the company had disposed of its lighterage fleet, it retained craft for its dredging activities. It was these vessels,<ref name=thamestugs/> its tugs and barges, that were represented within the [[Merchant Navy (United Kingdom)|merchant marine]] fleet that took part in Operation Dynamo, commonly known as the [[Dunkirk evacuation]] during [[World War II]], when in late May and early June 1940 a [[flotilla]] of 700 ships and boats assisted in the [[rescue]] and [[repatriation]] of the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|British Expeditionary Force]] (BEF) and [[French Army|French troops]].<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=uJgxAAAACAAJ&dq=B.E.F.Ships+Before,+at+and+After+Dunkirk |title=B. E. F. Ships Before, at and After Dunkirk |year=1999 |author1=Winser, John De S. |accessdate=7 March 2013 |isbn=978-0905617916 |publisher=World Ship Society |location =Chatham, Kent, UK}}</ref> Amongst this fleet of ships and boats was the company's dredger ''Gallions Reach'', originally built in 1936 as a steam hopper, but converted at the outbreak of war to a salvage vessel,<ref>[http://www.leithshipyards.com/ships-built-in-leith/1918-to-1939/298-gallions-reach-yard-no-229-steam-hopper-dredger-tilbury-contracting-a-dredging-co-built-1936.html Ships built in Leith] Leith Shipyards website Retrieved 17 March 2013</ref> this vessel rescued 123 men from the beaches and returned them to England.<ref>[http://www.thamestugs.co.uk/DUNKIRK.php Dunkirk] Thames Tugs History Website Retrieved 17 March 2013</ref>\n\n====Operation Neptune====\nOn 6 June 1944 company tug ''Danube VI'', under COTUG (Control Tug Operation),<ref>[http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/UN/UK/LondonGazette/38110.pdf \"Despatch submitted to the Supreme Commander, Allied Expeditionary Force on the 16th October, 1944, by Admiral Sir Bertram H. Ramsay, K.C.B., M.V.O., Allied Naval Commander-in-Chief, Expeditionary Force\"] Published in the ''London Gazette'' Tuesday 28 October 1947, Retrieved 17 March 2013</ref> participated in Operation Neptune, the D-Day invasion of Normandy, known as the [[Normandy landings]] by towing the 'Phoenix' ([[mulberry harbour]] breakwater units) and 'Whale' (floating roadway units that connected the mulberry harbour pier heads to the landing beaches),<ref>[http://www.thamestugs.co.uk/MULBERRY-TUGS-%5B1%5D.php Mulberry Tugs] Thames Tugs History Website Retrieved 17 March 2013</ref> as well as ammunition barges from [[Littlehampton]] across the English Channel to the Normandy beachhead.<ref name=thamestugs/>\n\n====Operation Pluto====\nCompany tug ''Danube V'' took part in pipelaying activities during July 1944, as part of [[Operation Pluto]],<ref name=thamestugs/> which brought together British scientists, oil companies and the [[armed forces]] in the construction of undersea oil pipelines under the English Channel between England and France to transport fuel supplies to [[Allies of World War II|Allied forces]] on the [[Europe]]an [[continent]].\n\n===Post war to stock market listing \u2013 1946 to 1960s===\nAs the UK sought to rebuild infrastructure after the Second World War, the company established a [[civil engineering]] capability in the 1940s to participate in this activity; together with building these had become the company's focus by the 1960s.<ref name=profile/> In 1964 the [[Port of London Authority]] dredging contract ended, 76 years after it was first awarded, and the company ceased to operate as a dredging contractor in the UK.<ref name=history/> In 1965 the remaining fleet of dredging vessels was sold to Westminster Dredging Company Limited.<ref name=thamestugs/> The company, by then named '''Tilbury Contracting Group Limited''',<ref name=history/> applied for admission of its shares onto the London Stock Exchange and trading commenced on 12 October 1966.<ref name=profile/>\n\n===Acquisition of R M Douglas Holdings and expansion into the Middle East \u2013 1990s===\nIn 1991 Tilbury acquired RM Douglas, another construction and civil engineering business, the combined business becoming known as '''Tilbury Douglas'''.<ref name=history/> Although both groups had a UK-wide presence, the rationale of the acquisition was that the two companies complemented each other. Tilbury Group was headquartered in Reading and predominantly involved in building work in the [[South of England]] and in Scotland, while R M Douglas was headquartered in [[Birmingham]] and its strongest regional presence was in the [[The Midlands, England|Midlands]] and the [[North of England]] with a strong bias towards civil engineering projects.\n\nIn common with many major national and regional [[contractors]] in the [[post-war]] period, R M Douglas successfully bid for work in the construction of [[aerodrome|airfields]] and [[controlled-access highway|motorways]] where it completed various UK motorway building projects in the 1960s, 1970s and 1980s.\n\nThe acquisition of Douglas also brought with it the construction equipment company [[RMD Kwikform|Rapid Metal Developments]] (RMD) a [[formwork]] and [[falsework]] manufacturer, together with [[joint venture]]s in [[Oman]] (Douglas OHI)<ref>[http://www.douglasohi.com/ Douglas OHI > Home<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and [[United Arab Emirates]] (Khansaheb),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://khansaheb.ae/page.php?pageid=9|title=Khansaheb Civil Engineering - UAE: History|work=khansaheb.ae|accessdate=22 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141126220310/http://www.khansaheb.ae/page.php?pageid=9|archive-date=26 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> both of which were initially established by Douglas in 1981.<ref name=history/> This expanded the geographical coverage of the company to the [[Middle East]] and this presence was further strengthened by the establishment of a joint venture in [[Qatar]] (Gulf Contracting Company).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gulfcontracting.com/aboutus.php?pid=1 |title=Message from Chairman of Gulf Contracting Co W.L.L. |access-date=21 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130310043432/http://www.gulfcontracting.com/aboutus.php?pid=1 |archive-date=10 March 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Diversification and name change \u2013 late 1990s and early 2000s===\nA series of acquisitions and [[Divestiture|disposals]] in the late 1990s and 2000 moved the group's focus away from [[property development]] and [[housebuilding]], as it sought to build presence in the [[Property maintenance|maintenance]] and [[facilities management]] sectors, though it retained a strong presence in traditional construction contracting. Acquisitions included electrical engineering contractor J R Williams in 1997,<ref>[https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/archive/tilbury-eyes-growth-with-me-move-02-10-1997/ Tilbury eyes growth with mechanical & electrical move] Construction News, 2 October 1997</ref> the facilities management and engineering services business How Group purchased for \u00a346m in 1998,<ref>[https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/archive/big-plans-for-maintenance-and-me-if-46-million-takeover-offer-is-accepted-tilbury-to-launch-fm-giant-from-how-deal-21-05-1998/ Big plans for maintenance and M&E if \u00a346 million takeover offer is accepted Tilbury to launch FM giant from How deal] Construction News, 21 May 1998</ref> the \u00a375m takeover of industrial and equipment services specialist Bandt Group in 1999<ref>[https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/archive/group-strengthens-its-support-services-position-with-agreed-75m-takeover-offer-tilbury-douglas-tunes-to-fm-with-bandt-deal-15-07-1999/ Group strengthens its support services position with agreed \u00a375m takeover offer Tilbury Douglas tunes to FM with Bandt deal] Construction News, 15 July 1999</ref> and, in a \u00a375m purchase, facilities management company Building and Property, responsible for providing accommodation and property services to [[government departments]].<ref>[http://citywire.co.uk/money/tilbury-douglas-in-75m-acquisition/a216793 Tilbury Douglas in \u00a375m acquisition] Citywire Money 15 December 2000</ref>\n\nDuring this period the company disposed of its Scottish housebuilding business to [[Persimmon plc]], diminishing the significance of revenues from traditional construction contracting workstreams,<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.interserve.com/media/financereports/Annual_Results_announcement_2001.pdf|title=Annual Results announcement 2001|work=interserve.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> with the newly diversified group now earning significant revenue through its facilities management and maintenance capability, which are otherwise known as support services provision.<ref name=history/> To reflect this change in the company's business profile, it successfully applied in 2000 to the [[London Stock Exchange]] to relinquish its listing within the construction sector of the market, but to re-list within the support services sector on the [[FTSE Group|FTSE]] market list.<ref name=history/><ref>[https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/archive/contractors-queueing-up-to-take-a-supporting-role-12-04-2001/ Contractors queueing up to take a supporting role] Construction News, 12 April 2001</ref> To reflect this change it renamed itself '''Interserve''' in 2001.<ref name=history/>\n\n===Acquisition of MacLellan and Madina Group \u2013 2000s===\nOn 2 May 2006 Interserve acquired MacLellan, another support services business for \u00a3118m.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/markets/questor/2938018/The-Questor-column.html Interserve's smart move sets pace for future expansion] The Daily Telegraph 3 May 2006</ref><ref>[http://www.interserve.com/news-media/press-releases-and-news/2006/05/02/209/cash-a-share-of-maclellan-group Recommended Cash and Share Acquisition of MacLellan Group Plc] Company website 2 May 2006 Retrieved 12 March 2013</ref> After re-structuring to accommodate the acquisition,<ref>[http://www.interserve.com/news-media/press-releases-and-news/2006/07/20/203/acquisition-change Acquisition, Organisational Update and Directorate Change] Company website 20 July 2006 Retrieved 12 March 2013</ref> Interserve announced it had discovered accounting irregularities in its Industrial Services business - an announcement that saw its share price fall by 14%.<ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/4eba9000-2b6d-11db-a7e1-0000779e2340.html#axzz2NK68tJLQ Interserve shares hit by accounting woes] Financial Times 14 August 2009 Retrieved 12 March 2013</ref> This decline led to threats of legal action by former MacLellan shareholders, who had accepted shares in Interserve as part of the acquisition and saw the value of their holdings dramatically drop.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/2945701/Shareholders-consider-suing-Interserve-over-accounts-error.html Shareholders consider suing Interserve over accounts error] The Daily Telegraph 18 August 2006 Retrieved 12 March 2013</ref> The company was also forced to delay the official publication of its interim results to investors, so as \"to verify the adjustment needed\" as it sought to reconcile the misstatements.<ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/448f34c4-349f-11db-bf9a-0000779e2340.html#axzz2NK68tJLQ Inquiry forces Interserve results delay] Financial Times 26 August 2006 Retrieved 12 March 2013</ref>\n\nIn 2007 the group acquired a 49% stake in the Qatar-based Madina Group.<ref name=history/><ref>[http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Interserve+to+buy+Madina+Group%3B+MANUFACTURING.-a0163363312 Interserve to buy Madina Group] The Birmingham Post 15 May 2007</ref> In 2008 Interserve expanded into markets in Abu Dhabi and Northern Europe.<ref name=history/>\n\n===Further acquisition activity \u2013 2010s===\nInterserve announced in November 2010 that it had acquired the US formwork and shoring business CMC Construction Services in a deal worth \u00a322 million.<ref>[https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/archive/interserve-expands-in-us-with-22m-deal-24-11-2010/ Interserve expands in US with \u00a322m deal] Construction News, 24 November 2010</ref> On 25 February 2011 the company emerged as a bidder for fellow support services provider, [[Mouchel]], as Interserve aimed to \"target the rapidly growing market for fully integrated outsourcing services.\" Interserve had approached the target with an offer believed to be in the region of \u00a3191m, or 170p per share; Mouchel had previously rejected two bids from [[Costain]].<ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/263582ee-4052-11e0-9140-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2NK68tJLQ Interserve expected to disclose Mouchel tie-up] Financial Times 25 February 2011 Retrieved 12 March 2013</ref><ref>[http://uk.reuters.com/article/2011/02/25/uk-mouchel-interserve-idUKTRE71O0ER20110225 Interserve (IRV.L) is in advanced talks with Mouchel MCHL.L over a tie-up that would create one of Britain's biggest public sector outsourcing companies, the Financial Times said on Friday] Reuters website 25 February 2011 Retrieved 12 March 2013</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/business/marketforceslive/2011/feb/25/mouchel-higher-interserve-bid Mouchel moves higher as Interserve confirms bid talks] The Guardian Market Forces Live Blog 25 February 2011 Retrieved 12 March 2013</ref><ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-25/interserve-in-advanced-talks-with-mouchel-about-possible-bid.html Interserve in Advanced Talks With Mouchel About Possible Bid] Bloomberg website 25 February 2011 Retrieved 12 March 2013</ref> However, after conducting due diligence on the consulting group, Interserve reduced its indicative offer to a reported \u00a3151m, or 135p per share, and this was subsequently rejected. Interserve did not progress the bid and no formal offer was tabled.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/supportservices/8414547/Mouchel-plunges-as-it-rejects-takeover-offers.html Mouchel plunges as it rejects takeover offers] The Daily Telegraph 29 March 2011 Retrieved 12 March 2013</ref><ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/f6c61646-5a36-11e0-86d3-00144feab49a.html#axzz2NK68tJLQ Interserve lowers Mouchel offer] Financial Times 29 March 2011 Retrieved 12 March 2013</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-12890542 Mouchel shares slump as takeover bids rejected] BBC News website 17 October 2011 Retrieved 12 March 2013</ref>\n\nOn 4 May 2012 the company acquired \"Welfare-to-work\" provider Business Employment Services Training (BEST), a UK provider of [[training]] and development for job-seekers and [[employers]].<ref>[http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2012/05/04/interserve-buys-training-company-for-17-5m/ Interserve buys training company for \u00a317.5m] Construction Enquirer, 4 May 2012</ref> Then on 12 October 2012 Interserve announced that it had sold its stakes in some UK [[private finance initiative]] hospitals, schools and prisons for \u00a390m. Dalmore Capital Fund, a UK infrastructure fund, agreed to buy 19 of the PFI investments, which generated \u00a34.6m profits for the group in 2011. The ''Financial Times'' reported the sale as including \"the stakes are five in hospitals \u2013 including University College London, Carlisle and Newcastle \u2013 five in schools, two in prisons and several in defence establishments.\"<ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/3938bcb6-1478-11e2-8ef2-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2MqzNnTmP Interserve sells PFI stakes for \u00a390m] Financial Times 12 October 2012</ref><ref>[https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/news/financial-news/interserve-sells-off-89-5m-in-pfi-stakes-12-10-2012/ Interserve sells off \u00a389.5m in PFI stakes] Construction News, 12 October 2012</ref> On 18 December 2012 it was announced that the company had acquired Advantage Healthcare, a leading UK provider of [[healthcare]] at home services for  \u00a326.5m in cash.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/supportservices/9753868/Interserve-buys-Advantage-Healthcare-for-26.5m.html Interserve buys Advantage Healthcare for \u00a326.5m] The Daily Telegraph, 18 December 2012</ref> Then on 7 January 2013 the organisation announced the acquisition of The Oman Construction Company for a cash consideration of $34.1m.<ref>[http://www.arabianoilandgas.com/article-10874-interserve-buys-the-oman-construction-company/#.UR1wFqU3Z_c Interserve buys The Oman Construction Company] Arabian Oil and Gas, 10 January 2013</ref>\n\nOn 28 February 2014, the company acquired Initial Facilities from [[Rentokil Initial]] for \u00a3250m.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/interserve-to-buy-rentokils-fm-business|title= Interserve to buy Rentokil's FM business|date= 28 February 2014|publisher=Construction Index|accessdate=29 June 2014}}</ref> In October 2014, Interserve benefitted from the UK Government's privatisation of the [[probation]] sector, securing contracts to run criminal justice services in five areas.<ref name=\"Travis-29Oct2014\">{{cite news |last1=Travis |first1=Alan |title=Two companies to run more than half of privatised probation services |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/oct/29/justice-probation-contracts-private-companies |accessdate=16 May 2019 |work=Guardian |date=29 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC-05Dec2014\">{{cite news |title=Probation contracts awarded to private organisations |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-30344262 |accessdate=16 May 2019 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2017-2019 financial difficulties===\nOn 14 September 2017, Interserve reported additional costs associated with quitting the energy-from-waste (EfW) sector. In February 2017, these costs were revised from \u00a370m to \u00a3160m; in September 2017, the figure had risen \"significantly\" but no new estimate was given<ref name=\"TCI-16Oct2017\">{{cite news|title=Interserve in bank talks|url=http://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/interserve-in-bank-talks|accessdate=16 October 2017|work=The Construction Index|date=16 October 2017}}</ref> (in March 2018, the developer of a [[Glasgow]] EfW plant said it was in \"ongoing\" discussions with Interserve after costs rose by \u00a395m to \u00a3250m, with [[Viridor]] contractually entitled to recover incremental costs from Interserve.)<ref name=\"Prior-27Mar2018\">{{cite news|last1=Prior|first1=Grant|title=Costs soar by \u00a395m at former Interserve energy plant|url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/03/27/costs-soar-by-95m-at-former-interserve-energy-plant/|accessdate=27 March 2018|work=Construction Enquirer|date=27 March 2018}}</ref> The company's lenders, including [[HSBC]] and [[Royal Bank of Scotland]], called in accountants [[Ernst & Young|EY]] to advise,<ref name=\"TCI-16Oct2017\"/> while the company appointed a new finance director, Mark Whiteling,<ref name=\"Curry-18Sep2017\">{{cite news|last1=Curry|first1=Rhiannon|title=Interserve hires finance director days after devastating profit warning|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/09/18/interserve-hires-finance-director-days-devastating-profit-warning/|accessdate=29 January 2018|work=Telegraph|date=18 September 2017}}</ref> to work alongside [[Debbie White (businesswoman)|Debbie White]], CEO from 1 September 2017.<ref name=\"TCI-01Sep2017\">{{cite news|title=New chief executive takes over at Interserve|url=http://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/new-chief-executive-takes-over-at-interserve|accessdate=29 January 2018|work=The Construction Index|date=1 September 2017}}</ref> On 19 October, the firm was reported to be \"battling for survival\" after warning it would breach bank loan covenants;<ref name=\"Morby-19Oct2017\">{{cite news|last1=Morby|first1=Aaron|title=Interserve is battling for survival after warning this morning it is now set to breach its bank loan covenants.|url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2017/10/19/interserve-likely-to-breach-bank-loan-covenants/|accessdate=20 October 2017|work=Construction Enquirer|date=19 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"TCI-19Oct2017\">{{cite news|title=Interserve on verge of breaching financial covenants|url=http://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/interserve-on-verge-of-breaching-financial-covenants|accessdate=20 October 2017|work=The Construction Index|date=19 October 2017}}</ref> shares slumped 38% to 55p, valuing the company at just \u00a380m,<ref name=\"Morby-19Oct2017\" /> before recovering to close at 65p.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.finance.yahoo.com/quote/IRV.L/history?p=IRV.L|title=Interserve|publisher=Yahoo Finance|accessdate=26 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 October 2017, the company was awarded a \u00a3227 million contract to provide facilities management services to the [[Department for Work and Pensions]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/10/20/struggling-interserve-bags-227m-government-contract/|title=Struggling Interserve bags \u00a3227m Government contract|last=Bury|first=Rhiannon|date=2017-10-20|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2017-10-20|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> On 13 November, Interserve was set to axe 200 jobs in a cost-cutting drive,<ref name=\"Prior-13Nov2017\">{{cite news|last1=Prior|first1=Grant|title=Interserve to axe 200 jobs in cost cutting drive|url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2017/11/13/interserve-to-axe-200-jobs-in-cost-cutting-drive/|accessdate=13 November 2017|work=Construction Enquirer|date=13 November 2017}}</ref> with further job losses expected.<ref name=\"Prior-15Nov2017\">{{cite news|last1=Prior|first1=Grant|url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2017/11/15/interserve-staff-braced-for-more-redundancies/|accessdate=15 November 2017|work=Construction Enquirer|title=Interserve staff braced for more redundancies}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 December 2017, it was reported that Interserve had secured \u00a3180m in short-term funding from its banks and had pushed back the test date for compliance with loan covenants to March 2018.<ref name=\"Morby-14Dec2017\">{{cite news|last1=Morby|first1=Aaron|title=Interserve seals \u00a3180m lending deal for extra headroom|url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2017/12/14/interserve-seals-180m-lending-deal-for-extra-headroom/|accessdate=14 December 2017|work=Construction Enquirer|date=14 December 2017}}</ref> Interserve also appointed a rescue specialist, Scott Millar, as chief restructuring officer.<ref name=\"TCI-15Dec2017\">{{cite news|title=Interserve denies banks forced company doctor appointment|url=http://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/interserve-denies-banks-forced-company-doctor-appointment|accessdate=15 December 2017|work=The Construction Index|date=15 December 2017}}</ref> On 10 January 2018, Interserve warned that its debt was set to rise above \u00a3513m at the year-end due to redundancy costs and cash outflows from its legacy EfW projects.<ref name=\"Morby-10Jan2018\">{{cite news|last1=Morby|first1=Grant|title=Interserve rescue on track but debt to rise above \u00a3500m|url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/01/10/interserve-debt-set-to-rise-above-500m/|accessdate=10 January 2018|work=Construction Enquirer|date=10 January 2018}}</ref> Following the January 2018 collapse of [[Carillion]], the ''[[Financial Times]]'' said Interserve was being monitored by the UK Government;<ref name=\"Pickard-17Jan2018\">{{cite news|last1=Pickard|first1=Jim|last2=Smith|first2=Robert|last3=Plimmer|first3=Gill|title=Interserve under government watch over financial health fears|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1aa17614-fab7-11e7-a492-2c9be7f3120a|accessdate=17 January 2018|work=Financial Times|date=17 January 2018}}</ref> the report led to a 15% drop in Interserve's share price, later largely recouped - a market analyst said: \"in the case of Interserve the arithmetic doesn't look anything like as bad as Carillion\".<ref name=\"Reuters-17Jan2018\">{{cite news|last1=Ponthus|first1=Julien|last2=Rees|first2=Kit|title=FTSE edges down, Interserve wobbles in post-Carillion scare|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-stocks/ftse-edges-down-interserve-wobbles-in-post-carillion-scare-idUKKBN1F610H?feedType=RSS&feedName=topNews|accessdate=17 January 2018|work=Reuters|date=17 January 2018}}</ref> Market uncertainty following Carillion's liquidation continued, partly fuelled by a 30 January profits warning by [[Capita]], after which Interserve's share price dropped nearly 20%.<ref name=\"BBC-01Feb2018\">{{cite news|title=Interserve shares slide amid Capita woes|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-42902065|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 February 2018, accountancy firm [[Deloitte]] was drafted in advise ministers on public sector contracts held by Interserve.<ref name=\"Sky-12Feb2018\">{{cite news|last1=Kleinman|first1=Mark|title=Whitehall taps Deloitte to monitor troubled outsourcer Interserve|url=https://news.sky.com/story/whitehall-taps-deloitte-to-monitor-troubled-outsourcer-interserve-11247637|accessdate=21 February 2018|work=Sky News|date=12 February 2018}}</ref> On 21 February, Interserve announced it was closing its power lines business, putting over 70 staff at risk of redundancy.<ref name=\"Morby-21Feb2018\">{{cite news|last1=Morby|first1=Aaron|title=Interserve to close power lines operation axing over 70 jobs|url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/02/21/interserve-to-close-power-lines-operation-axing-over-70-jobs/|accessdate=21 February 2018|work=Construction Enquirer|date=21 February 2018}}</ref> Three days later, Interserve was said to be struggling to agree a debt refinancing deal because Carillion's liquidation had spooked lenders;<ref name=\"Marlow-24Feb2018\">{{cite news|last1=Marlow|first1=Ben|title=Interserve crisis grows as debt talks stumble|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2018/02/24/interserve-crisis-grows-debt-talks-stumble/|accessdate=25 February 2018|work=Telegraph|date=24 February 2018}}</ref> Interserve denied the talks had stumbled.<ref name=\"Gill-25Feb2018\">{{cite news|last1=Gill|first1=Oliver|title=Interserve hits back by insisting refinancing has not \"stumbled\" and talks are proceeding on time|url=http://www.cityam.com/281202/interserve-share-price-hits-back-insisting-refinancing-has-not-stumbled|accessdate=26 February 2018|work=City AM|date=25 February 2018}}</ref> On 26 February, Interserve's share price fell 12% to close at 57p.<ref name=\"LSE-26Feb\">{{cite web|title=IRV INTERSERVE PLC ORD 10P|url=http://www.londonstockexchange.com/exchange/prices-and-markets/stocks/summary/company-summary/GB0001528156GBGBXSSMM.html?lang=en|website=London Stock Exchange|accessdate=26 February 2018}}</ref> On 3 March, Emerald Investment Partners, the family firm of [[Punch Taverns]] founder Alan McIntosh, acquired \u00a3140m of Interserve debts on secondary markets in a bid to save the company.<ref name=\"Marlow-03Mar2018\">{{cite news|last1=Marlow|first1=Ben|title=Scottish multi-millionaire plots rescue of Interserve after quietly amassing outsourcer's debt|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2018/03/03/scottish-multi-millionaire-plots-rescue-interserve-quietly-amassing/|accessdate=5 March 2018|work=Telegraph|date=3 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Gill-04Mar2018\">{{cite news|last1=Gill|first1=Oliver|title=Interserve rescue plans boosted by white knight's \u00a3140m debt trade|url=http://www.cityam.com/281608/interserve-rescue-plans-boosted-white-knights-gbp140m-debt|accessdate=5 March 2018|work=City AM|date=4 March 2018}}</ref> Interserve was reported to have cut 500 administrative staff in the last quarter and to be planning a further 1,000 job losses by the end of 2018.<ref name=\"Plimmer-04Mar2018\">{{cite news|last1=Plimmer|first1=Gill|title=Interserve plans further job cuts as it fights bankruptcy fears|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f235a57c-1f93-11e8-9efc-0cd3483b8b80|accessdate=5 March 2018|work=Financial Times|date=4 March 2018}}</ref> On 8 March, a series of equity swap deals bolstered Interserve's share price;<ref name=\"Gill-08Mar2018\">{{cite news|last1=Gill|first1=Oliver|title=Interserve shares rocket almost 50 per cent|url=http://www.cityam.com/281948/interserve-shares-rocket-almost-50-per-cent|accessdate=11 March 2018|work=City AM|date=8 March 2018}}</ref> the following day Interserve put its stake in the \u00a3200m [[Haymarket, Edinburgh|Haymarket]] development in [[Edinburgh]] up for sale to help reduce its near \u00a3600m debts.<ref name=\"Morby-09Mar2018\">{{cite news|last1=Morby|first1=Aaron|title=Interserve to offload stake in Edinburgh Haymarket scheme|url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/03/09/interserve-to-offload-stake-in-edinburgh-harmarket-scheme/|accessdate=11 March 2018|work=Construction Enquirer|date=9 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018 financial restructuring====\nOn 21 March 2018 Interserve announced it had agreed commercial terms with its main bankers for extra cash facilities of \u00a3197m and fresh bonding facilities up to \u00a395m.<ref name=\"Morby-21Mar2018\">{{cite news|last1=Morby|first1=Aaron|title=Interserve finally agrees refinancing deal with banks|url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/03/21/interserve-finally-agrees-refinancing-deal-with-banks/|accessdate=21 March 2018|work=Construction Enquirer|date=21 March 2018}}</ref> Lenders agreed a further 30-day extension for completion of the refinancing paperwork<ref name=\"TCI-22Mar2018\">{{cite news|title=Interserve granted 30 more days to finalise refinancing|url=http://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/interserve-granted-30-more-days-to-finalise-refinancing|accessdate=22 March 2018|work=The Construction Index|date=22 March 2018}}</ref> (concluded on 27 April).<ref name=\"Plimmer-30Apr2018\">{{cite news|last1=Plimmer|first1=Gill|title=Interserve shares tumble on widening losses|url=https://www.ft.com/content/ca3266ae-4c49-11e8-8a8e-22951a2d8493|accessdate=30 April 2018|work=Financial Times|date=30 April 2018}}</ref> The refinancing news drove shares up almost 26% to 87.9p.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2018/mar/21/interserve-agrees-refinancing-deal-ease-fears-future|title=Interserve agrees refinancing deal to ease fears over its future|last=Kollewe|first=Julia|date=2018-03-21|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> However, the share price tumbled 13% in early trading on 30 April after Interserve reported a \u00a3244m loss for 2017, with debts almost doubled from \u00a3274m to \u00a3502.6m; analysts anticipated a possible sell-off of Interserve's international support services and construction divisions.<ref name=\"Plimmer-30Apr2018\"/> On 11 May, Interserve said it would be investigated by the [[Financial Conduct Authority]] with regard to handling of inside information and market disclosures regarding its EfW business.<ref name=\"Price-11May2018\">{{cite news|last1=Price|first1=David|title=Interserve under investigation over EfW disclosure|url=https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/news/contractors-news/interserve-under-investigation-over-efw-disclosure-11-05-2018/|accessdate=11 May 2018|work=Construction News|date=11 May 2018}}</ref> On 31 May, the operator of the Glasgow EfW scheme claimed Interserve owed \u00a369m in additional costs;<ref name=\"Rogers-31May2018\">{{cite news |last1=Rogers |first1=Dave |title=Interserve told it owes \u00a369m on Glasgow waste job |url=https://www.building.co.uk/news/interserve-told-it-owes-69m-on-glasgow-waste-job/5093850.article |accessdate=31 May 2018 |work=Building |date=31 May 2018}}</ref> in November 2018, Viridor said it expected to receive at least \u00a364m from Interserve.<ref name=\"Morby-27Nov2018\">{{cite news |last1=Morby |first1=Aaron |title=Interserve faces \u00a364m claim for Glasgow waste facility completion |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/11/27/interserve-faces-64m-claim-for-glasgow-waste-facility-completion/ |accessdate=27 November 2018 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=27 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nInterserve reported its half-year results on 7 August 2018. These showed a pre-tax loss of \u00a36m, said 470 jobs were lost, and showed revenue dipping to \u00a31,488m from \u00a31,647m.<ref name=\"Prior-7Aug2018\">{{cite news |last1=Prior |first1=Grant |title=More losses at Interserve as debt levels top \u00a3600m |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/08/07/more-losses-at-interserve-as-debt-levels-top-600m/ |accessdate=7 August 2018 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=7 August 2018}}</ref> Legacy EfW contracts dragged results down, but Interserve aimed to complete and hand over problem EfW contracts by the end of 2018 (in January 2019, ''[[New Civil Engineer]]'' reported that handover would happen in the first half of 2019).<ref name=\"Sholli-04Jan2019\">{{cite news |last1=Sholli |first1=Sam |title=Interserve EfW plant handovers due later than expected |url=https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/interserve-efw-plant-handovers-due-later-than-expected/10038595.article? |accessdate=8 January 2019 |work=New Civil Engineer |date=4 January 2019}}</ref> The business suffered a \u00a36.6m loss from exiting the London construction business, and incurred \u00a310.8m in restructuring costs and \u00a332.1m in 'professional adviser fees' in connection with its refinancing. Net debt at 30 June was \u00a3614.3m, with Interserve expected to pay \u00a380m in interest costs in 2018.<ref name=\"Prior-7Aug2018\"/>\n\nOn 13 November 2018, concerns about an EfW project in [[Derby]] led to a 30% slide to a 34-year low (29p) in Interserve's share price,<ref name=\"Ing-13Nov2018\">{{cite news |last1=Ing |first1=Will |title=Interserve's share price tanks on back of Derby waste woe |url=https://www.building.co.uk/news/interserves-share-price-tanks-on-back-of-derby-waste-woe/5096542.article |accessdate=13 November 2018 |work=Building |date=13 November 2018}}</ref> though it later ended down just 10% on the day.<ref name=\"Morby-14Nov2018\">{{cite news |last1=Morby |first1=Aaron |title=Interserve fights to quell stock market jitters |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/11/14/interserve-fights-to-quell-stock-market-jitters/ |accessdate=14 November 2018 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=14 November 2018}}</ref> A critic blamed its problems on ill-timed acquisitions, expansion into areas (probation, healthcare, EfW) where it had no experience, and a weak [[balance sheet]] (of \u00a3427.4m intangibles on its balance sheet, \u00a3372.9m was [[Goodwill (accounting)|goodwill]]).<ref name=\"Plimmer-14Nov2018\">{{cite news |last1=Plimmer |first1=Gill |title=Interserve concerns prompt fears of fresh outsourcing crisis |url=https://www.ft.com/content/66fbadd2-e72d-11e8-8a85-04b8afea6ea3 |accessdate=14 November 2018 |work=Financial Times |date=14 November 2018}}</ref> In a 23 November trading update, CEO Debbie White said the group would unveil plans to tackle its debt mountain in early 2019 after revealing year-end net debt would be worse than expected, up to \u00a3625m-\u00a3650m due to additional cash outflows on EfW projects and slow payments in Middle Eastern markets.<ref name=\"Morby-23Nov2018\">{{cite news |last1=Morby |first1=Aaron |title=Interserve to roll-out \u00a3650m debt reduction plan |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/11/23/interserve-to-roll-out-650m-debt-reduction-plan/ |accessdate=23 November 2018 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=23 November 2018}}</ref> The news pushed down shares 9% (closing at 33p),<ref name=\"Plimmer-23Nov2018\">{{cite news |last1=Plimmer |first1=Gill |last2=Hodgson |first2=Camilla |title=Interserve sparks concerns as debts rise |url=https://www.ft.com/content/b2c9fdd2-eeed-11e8-8180-9cf212677a57 |accessdate=26 November 2018 |work=Financial Times |date=23 November 2018}}</ref> and there was further pressure on 26 November when [[West Yorkshire Police]] said it would be seeking compensation for faults in construction of custody suites in [[Leeds]] and [[Wakefield]].<ref name=\"Ing-26Nov2018\">{{cite news |last1=Ing |first1=Will |title=Interserve facing fresh woe after problems hit West Yorks police job |url=https://www.building.co.uk/news/interserve-facing-fresh-woe-after-problems-hit-west-yorks-police-job/5096745.article |accessdate=26 November 2018 |work=Building |date=26 November 2018}}</ref> Interserve shares closed on 30 November down 6.5% at 28p.<ref name=\"LSE-30Nov2018\">{{cite news |last1=McGowan |first1=Paul |title=WINNERS & LOSERS SUMMARY: FLYBE UP 37% ON VIRGIN ATLANTIC BID REPORT |url=https://www.londonstockexchange.com/exchange/news/alliance-news/detail/1542969362217034300.html |accessdate=30 November 2018 |work=London Stock Exchange: Alliance News |date=30 November 2018}}</ref> The share price slide continued into December (closing at 21p on 4 December), after, in ''[[Building (magazine)|Building]]'', [[Specialist Engineering Contractors Group]] CEO Rudi Klein advised members not to work for Interserve if possible.<ref name=\"Ing-03Dec2018\">{{cite news |last1=Ing |first1=Will |last2=Marshall |first2=Jordan |title=Trade body tells subbies to go to clients direct to get paid on Interserve jobs |url=https://www.building.co.uk/news/trade-body-tells-subbies-to-go-to-clients-direct-to-get-paid-on-interserve-jobs-/5096857.article |accessdate=3 December 2018 |work=Building |date=3 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Davies-03Dec2018\">{{cite news |last1=Davies |first1=Graeme |title=News & Tips: AstraZeneca, Royal Dutch Shell, Interserve & more |url=https://www.investorschronicle.co.uk/shares/2018/12/03/news-tips-astrazeneca-royal-dutch-shell-interserve-more/ |accessdate=3 December 2018 |work=Investors Chronicle |date=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Failed 2019 financial restructuring====\nOn 7 December 2018, Interserve was reported - for the second time in 2018 - to be in rescue refinancing talks, with banks and other debt holders (including RBS, HSBC, [[BNP Paribas]], Emerald Asset Management and [[Davidson Kempner Capital Management|Davidson Kempner Capital]]) preparing to incur losses in a debt-for-equity swap that would see public shareholders virtually wiped out.<ref name=\"Plimmer-07Dec2018\">{{cite news |last1=Plimmer |first1=Gill |last2=Elder |first2=Bryce |title=Interserve in fresh rescue talks with creditors |url=https://www.ft.com/content/dd8e5588-f8b9-11e8-af46-2022a0b02a6c |accessdate=9 December 2018 |work=Financial Times |date=7 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Ambrose-08Dec2018\">{{cite news |last1=Ambrose |first1=Gillian |title=Interserve lenders seek to wrest back control |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2018/12/08/interserve-lenders-seek-wrest-back-control/ |accessdate=9 December 2018 |work=Telegraph |date=8 December 2018}}</ref> On 10 December, Interserve confirmed its deleveraging plan could result in \"material dilution\" for current Interserve shareholders;<ref name=\"Grecenko-10Dec2018\">{{cite news |last1=Grecenko |first1=Evelina |title=INTERSERVE CONFIRMS DELEVERAGING PLAN TO RESULT IN \"MATERIAL DILUTION\" |url=https://www.londonstockexchange.com/exchange/news/alliance-news/detail/1544424742843297600.html |accessdate=10 December 2018 |work=London Stock Exchange - Alliance News |date=10 December 2018}}</ref> shares dived,<ref name=\"Morby-10Dec2018\">{{cite news |last1=Morby |first1=Aaron |title=Interserve shares collapse as rescue talks continue |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/12/09/interserve-makes-headway-on-rescue-talks/ |accessdate=10 December 2018 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=10 December 2018}}</ref> eventually closing 53% down at 11.5p.<ref name=\"Daniel-10Dec2018\">{{cite news |last1=Daniel |first1=Alex |title=Interserve share price plummets as it admits rescue refinancing plan |url=http://www.cityam.com/270335/interserve-share-price-plummets-admits-rescue-refinancing |accessdate=10 December 2018 |work=City AM |date=10 December 2018}}</ref> Fearing problems similar to those faced by clients after Carillion collapsed, the Labour Party urged the Government to bar Interserve from bidding for public contracts,<ref name=\"Prior-10Dec2018\">{{cite news |last1=Prior |first1=Grant |title=Labour calls for public contract bidding ban on Interserve |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/12/10/labour-calls-for-public-contract-bidding-ban-on-interserve/ |accessdate=10 December 2018 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=10 December 2018}}</ref> but the Cabinet Office insisted Interserve was different to Carillion.<ref name=\"Brady-12Dec2018\">{{cite news |last1=Brady |first1=Dominic |title=, but civil servants insisted Interserve was different to Carillion |url=https://www.publicfinance.co.uk/news/2018/12/interserve-not-another-carillion-says-manzoni? |accessdate=12 December 2018 |work=Public Finance |date=12 December 2018}}</ref> Meanwhile, Interserve announced a \u00a325m contract win at a Welsh hospital.<ref name=\"Kollewe-10Dec2018\">{{cite news |last1=Kollewe |first1=Julia |title=Outsourcing firm Interserve's shares dive by 75% despite rescue plan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2018/dec/10/interserve-shares-rescue-plan-carillion |accessdate=10 December 2018 |work=Guardian |date=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nRestructuring options included spinning off the \u00a3250m building materials unit [[RMD Kwikform]] to lenders, leaving the remainder of Interserve as a more focused support services business.<ref name=\"Kleinman-15Dec2018\">{{cite news |last1=Kleinman |first1=Mark |title=Struggling Interserve may hand construction unit to lenders |url=https://news.sky.com/story/struggling-interserve-may-hand-construction-unit-to-lenders-11581667 |accessdate=16 December 2018 |work=Sky News |date=15 December 2018}}</ref> The core principles of the deleveraging plan were reported to have been conditionally agreed between Interserve and its lenders on 21 December 2018,<ref name=\"TCi-21Dec2018\">{{cite news |title=Interserve pressed to surrender RMD Kwikform |url=https://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/interserve-pressed-to-surrender-rmd-kwikform |accessdate=21 December 2018 |work=The Construction Index |date=21 December 2018}}</ref> but negotiations continued through January 2019, with the deal, excluding sale of RMD Kwikform, reported to be close to announcement on 3 February.<ref name=\"Kleinman-3Feb2019\">{{cite news |last1=Kleinman |first1=Mark |title=Outsourcer Interserve closes in on debt-for-equity rescue deal |url=https://news.sky.com/story/outsourcer-interserve-closes-in-on-debt-for-equity-rescue-deal-11627404 |accessdate=4 February 2019 |work=Sky News |date=3 February 2019}}</ref> The Cabinet Office reportedly objected to any deal involving selling RMD Kwikform, believing this would render the remainder of the business almost worthless, making it difficult to continue awarding contracts to the company.<ref name=\"Davies-05Feb2019\">{{cite news |last1=Davies |first1=Rob |title=Interserve's lenders go head-to-head with Cabinet Office over rescue options |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/feb/05/interserves-lenders-go-head-to-head-with-cabinet-office-over-rescue-options |accessdate=5 February 2019 |work=Guardian |date=5 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 February, Interserve announced it had agreed a deleveraging deal with its lenders: it planned to raise \u00a3480m through a new share issue (accounting for 97.5% of the total issued share capital), reducing debts from over \u00a3600m to \u00a3275m, and retaining RMD Kwikform in the group. The plan was subject to approval by Interserve's shareholders, but Interserve was \"actively preparing alternative plans\" in case that approval was not given;<ref name=\"RNS-6Feb2019\">{{cite web |title=Progress on Deleveraging Plan |url=https://www.londonstockexchange.com/exchange/news/market-news/market-news-detail/IRV/13959523.html |website=London Stock Exchange RNS |accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC-6Feb2019\">{{cite news |title=Interserve agrees rescue plan with creditors |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-47141828 |accessdate=6 February 2019 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 February 2019}}</ref> [[Administration (law)|administration]] remained a possibility.<ref name=\"Daniel-10Feb2019\">{{cite news |last1=Daniel |first1=Alex |title=Out of the frying pan, Inter-the fire: Will Interserve's rescue deal go up in flames? |url=http://www.cityam.com/273025/out-frying-pan-inter-fire-interserves-rescue-deal-go-up |accessdate=11 February 2019 |work=City A.M. |date=10 February 2019}}</ref> One major shareholder, hedge fund Coltrane Asset Management, while supportive of the CEO, requisitioned an [[extraordinary general meeting]] (EGM) calling for the removal of eight other directors; another shareholder, Farringdon Capital Management, also voiced opposition to the proposed rescue plan.<ref name=\"Daniel-12Feb2019\">{{cite news |last1=Daniel |first1=Alex |title=Interserve rescue plan: Shareholder rebellion grows as dissenting hedge fund recruits another supporter |url=http://www.cityam.com/273153/interserve-rescue-plan-shareholder-rebellion-grows |accessdate=13 February 2019 |work=City A.M. |date=12 February 2019}}</ref> On 14 February, it was reported that blocking the deleveraging plan and removing key board members could trigger an immediate \u00a366m repayment to lenders, weakening Interserve's financial position still further.<ref name=\"Kleinman-14Feb2019\">{{cite news |last1=Kleinman |first1=Mark |title=Interserve faces debt bombshell over hedge fund coup |url=https://news.sky.com/story/interserve-faces-debt-bombshell-over-hedge-fund-coup-11637210 |accessdate=14 February 2019 |work=Sky News |date=14 February 2019}}</ref> On 20 February, Coltrane had grown its stake and now held 27.7% of Interserve's voting rights through publicly traded shares.<ref name=\"Daniel-20Feb2018\">{{cite news |last1=Daniel |first1=Alex |title=Interserve's rebel shareholder Coltrane ups stake in struggling outsourcer |url=http://www.cityam.com/273551/interserves-rebelling-lead-shareholder-tightens-grip-firm |accessdate=20 February 2019 |work=City A.M. |date=20 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=The Economist |url=https://www.economist.com/britain/2018/12/15/interserve-goes-to-intensive-care |title=Interserve goes to intensive care - Outsourcers in trouble |publisher=Economist.com |date=2018-12-13 |accessdate=2019-03-04}}</ref> In view of shareholders' opposition, on 22 February lenders were reported to be amending the debt-for-equity proposals so that existing shareholders would own 5% of Interserve.<ref name=\"Kleinman-22Feb2019\">{{cite news |last1=Kleinman |first1=Mark |title=Interserve lenders to sweeten terms of \u00a3500m rescue |url=https://news.sky.com/story/interserve-lenders-to-sweeten-terms-of-500m-rescue-11644662 |accessdate=22 February 2019 |work=Sky News |date=22 February 2019}}</ref> However, an alternative Coltrane proposal (retaining a 10% equity share for shareholders) had also been put to Interserve, while [[Ernst & Young|EY]] had been put on standby to act as administrator.<ref name=\"Davies-22Feb2019\">{{cite news |last1=Rob |first1=Davies |last2=Pratley |first2=Nils |title=Interserve lenders line up EY as administrator if shareholder talks fail |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/feb/22/interserve-lenders-line-up-ey-administrator-if-shareholder-talks-fail |accessdate=22 February 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=22 February 2019}}</ref> The proposals were to be subject to an EGM vote on 26 March,<ref name=\"Morby-26Feb2019\">{{cite news |last1=Morby |first1=Aaron |title=Interserve sets date for rescue plan showdown |url=https://www.constructionenquirer.com/2019/02/26/interserve-sets-date-rescue-plan-showdown/ |accessdate=27 February 2019 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=26 February 2019}}</ref> later brought forward to an [[annual general meeting|AGM]] vote on 15 March.<ref name=\"Davies-4Mar2019\">{{cite news |last1=Davies |first1=Rob |title=Interserve's largest shareholder issues rescue deal demand |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/mar/04/interserve-shareholder-rescue-deal |accessdate=4 March 2019 |work=Guardian |date=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February, Interserve announced its financial results for the year to 31 December 2018, recording a pre-tax loss of \u00a3111.5m on a turnover of \u00a32904m (down 10.7% due to a drop in UK construction activity and tighter bidding criteria). Net debt increased to \u00a3631.2m, and the company warned: \"successful implementation of the Deleveraging Plan is critical to our future.\" Professional fees for the 2018 refinancing totalled \u00a343m with a further \u00a333m set to be paid in connection with the deleveraging plan. A further \u00a312.6m in losses on problem EfW contracts brought the total loss to date to \u00a3229.2m.<ref name=\"Prior-27Feb2019\">{{cite news |last1=Prior |first1=Grant |title=Interserve makes \u00a3111m loss and spends \u00a376m on refinancing fees |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2019/02/27/interserve-makes-111m-loss-and-spends-76m-on-refinancing-fees/ |accessdate=27 February 2019 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=27 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nColtrane remained opposed to the deleveraging plan, angered by expenditure on the plans and by directors' reluctance to invest in new shares.<ref name=\"Davies-27Feb2019\">{{cite news |last1=Davies |first1=Rob |title=Interserve's biggest shareholder says rescue plan is 'terrible' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/feb/27/interserves-biggest-shareholder-says-rescue-plan-is-terrible |accessdate=27 February 2019 |work=Guardian |date=27 February 2019}}</ref> Interserve's \u00a390m expenditure on fees (to investment bank Rothschild investment bank, broker [[Numis]], lawyers [[Ashurst LLP]] and [[Slaughter and May]], accountant [[Grant Thornton International|Grant Thornton]] and PR firm Tulchan) was said to be equivalent to the cash the firm would have if its restructuring plan was successful with shareholders.<ref name=\"Lea-28Feb2019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/interserve-rescue-fees-hit-90m-x6qlvdqmt|title=Interserve rescue fees hit \u00a390m|last1=Lea|first1=Robert|date=28 February 2019|work=Times|accessdate=4 March 2019}}</ref> Coltrane called the sell-off to fund debts \"an obscenity,\"<ref name=\"Lea-28Feb2019\" /> and, on 4 March, submitted a revised financial rescue plan (giving 55% of the company to creditors, leaving shareholders with 37.5%) and told directors to stop advocating rival proposals put forward by the company's lenders<ref name=\"Davies-4Mar2019\" /> (Coltrane later threatened legal action against Interserve's directors to hold them personally accountable for the company's losses).<ref name=\"Graham-10MAr2019\">{{cite news |last1=Graham |first1=August |title=Interserve battles to avoid administration as shareholder vote looms on Friday |url=http://www.cityam.com/274433/interserve-battles-avoid-administration-shareholder-vote |accessdate=10 March 2019 |work=City A.M. |date=10 March 2019}}</ref> However, the Interserve board rejected this proposal,<ref name=\"Morby-5Mar2019\">{{cite news |last1=Morby |first1=Aaron |title=Interserve rejects second shareholder rescue plan |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2019/03/05/interserve-rejects-second-shareholder-rescue-plan/ |accessdate=5 March 2019 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=5 March 2019}}</ref> while lenders lined up a precautionary '[[Pre-packaged insolvency|pre-pack administration]]' that would wipe out existing shareholders but keep Interserve operating if the deleveraging plan was not approved.<ref name=\"Reuters-9Mar2019\">{{cite news |title=Interserve set for pre-pack administration if debt deal fails: source |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-interserve-debt-idUSKBN1QQ0MI |accessdate=9 March 2019 |work=Reuters |agency=Reuters |date=9 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, lenders tried a last-ditch effort to win shareholder support by increasing the amount of equity retained by shareholders to 7.5%,<ref name=\"Kleinman-11Mar2019\">{{cite news |last1=Kleinman |first1=Mark |title=Interserve lenders in talks about last-ditch deal sweetener |url=https://news.sky.com/story/interserve-lenders-in-talks-about-last-ditch-deal-sweetener-11662097 |accessdate=11 March 2019 |work=Sky News |date=11 March 2019}}</ref> but this was not backed by Interserve's board which urged support for the deleveraging plan offering shareholders 5%.<ref name=\"Morby-12Mar2019\">{{cite news |last1=Morby |first1=Aaron |title=Interserve warns shareholders not to expect better deal |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2019/03/12/interserve-warns-shareholders-not-to-expect-better-deal/ |accessdate=12 March 2019 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=12 March 2019}}</ref> Coltrane warned Interserve's prospective administrator against arranging a pre-pack insolvency deal, demanding rigorous and comprehensive marketing, and holding out the prospect that Coltrane might acquire the company from the insolvency process.<ref name=\"Kleinman-12Mar2019\">{{cite news |last1=Kleinman |first1=Mark |title=Top Interserve shareholder warns on asset sales |url=https://news.sky.com/story/top-interserve-shareholder-warns-on-asset-sales-11663029 |accessdate=12 March 2019 |work=Sky News |date=12 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Administration===\nAt the 15 March AGM, the deleveraging plan was rejected by shareholders,<ref name=\"Price-15Mar2019\">{{cite news |last1=Price |first1=David |last2=Garner-Purkis |first2=Zak |title=Interserve rescue plan voted down |url=https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/news/contractors-news/interserve-rescue-plan-voted-down-15-03-2019/ |accessdate=15 March 2019 |work=Construction News |date=15 March 2019}}</ref> and trading in the company's shares was suspended.<ref name=\"Morby-15Mar2019\">{{cite news |last1=Morby |first1=Aaron |title=Shareholders reject Interserve rescue plan |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2019/03/15/shareholders-reject-interserve-rescue-plan/ |accessdate=15 March 2019 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=15 March 2019}}</ref> Interserve's board confirmed it had applied for the parent company to be placed into administration, and said it was pursuing the pre-pack option.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/mar/15/interserve-to-go-into-administration-after-shareholders-reject-deal|title=Interserve goes into administration after rescue deal rejected|publisher=The Guardian|date=15 March 2019|accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref> The board later announced the group had been sold to a new company, to be called '''Interserve Group Ltd''', controlled by Interserve's existing lenders.<ref name=\"LSE-15Mar2019\">{{cite web |title=Successful completion of sale of the group (15 March 2019) |url=https://www.londonstockexchange.com/exchange/prices-and-markets/stocks/exchange-insight/company-news.html?fourWayKey=GB0001528156GBGBXSET3 |website=London Stock Exchange |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe administration and pre-pack process meant banks wrote off up to \u00a3800m in loans, while Coltrane, Farringdon and around 16,000 small shareholders all lost their investments. Unions and others expressed concern about the government's continued awarding of contracts to Interserve during its financial troubles, but a Cabinet Office spokesperson said its processes and financial check had been robust, adding: \"The refinancing process that Interserve executed led to the smooth continuation of public services and safeguarded thousands of jobs.\"<ref name=\"Brignall-18Mar2019\">{{cite news |last1=Brignall |first1=Miles |title=Interserve given 'public contracts worth \u00a3660m in run-up to collapse' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/mar/18/interserve-given-public-contracts-worth-660m-in-run-up-to-collapse |accessdate=18 March 2019 |work=Guardian |date=18 March 2019}}</ref> However, around 200 firms that provided IT, HR and property management services to Interserve plc risked not being paid.<ref name=\"Morby-18Mar2019\">{{cite news |last1=Morby |first1=Aaron |title=Interserve subcontractors told it's business as usual |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2019/03/18/interserve-subcontractors-told-its-business-as-usual/ |accessdate=18 March 2019 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=18 March 2019}}</ref> EfW client Viridor repeated its claim that, despite the administration, the still operating Interserve Construction owed \u00a364m for work on its Glasgow plant;<ref name=\"Rogers-18Mar2019\">{{cite news |last1=Rogers |first1=Dave |title='You still owe us \u00a364m,' says client who kicked Interserve off Glasgow waste job |url=https://www.building.co.uk/news/you-still-owe-us-64m-says-client-who-kicked-interserve-off-glasgow-waste-job/5098464.article |accessdate=24 March 2019 |work=Building |date=18 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Morby-25Mar2019\">{{cite news |last1=Morby |first1=Aaron |title=Interserve client fears bigger hit on Glasgow waste plant |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2019/03/25/interserve-client-fears-bigger-hit-on-glasgow-waste-plant/ |accessdate=25 March 2019 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=25 March 2019}}</ref> in November 2019, Viridor issued arbitration proceedings to reclaim \u00a372m.<ref name=\"TCI-26Nov2019\">{{cite news |title=Viridor-Interserve dispute moves to arbitration |url=https://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/viridor-interserve-dispute-moves-to-arbitration |accessdate=26 November 2019 |work=The Construction Index |date=26 November 2019}}</ref> In June 2019, it was reported that Interserve had collapsed owing creditors over \u00a3100m.<ref name=\"Ball-10Jun2019\">{{cite news |last1=Ball |first1=Frances |title=Interserve owed creditors more than \u00a3100m |url=https://economia.icaew.com/news/interserve-owed-creditors-more-than-100m |accessdate=10 June 2019 |work=Economia |publisher=ICAEW |date=10 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nRival outsourcing firms including [[Mitie]], [[Serco]] and [[Sodexo]] were reported to be considering bids to acquire Interserve's core support services business,<ref name=\"Waite-16Mar2019\">{{cite news |last1=Waite |first1=Suzie |title=Mitie Mulls Takeover Bid for Main Interserve Unit, Sky Reports |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-16/mitie-mulls-takeover-bid-for-main-interserve-unit-sky-reports |accessdate=16 March 2019 |work=Bloomberg |date=16 March 2019}}</ref> valued by lenders at around \u00a3300m.<ref name=\"Morby-18Mar2019\"/> Mitie was repeatedly reported to be considering a bid of about \u00a3100m for the support services arm, which employs about 40,000 of the Interserve group's 45,000-strong UK workforce.<ref name=\"Davies-18Mar2019\">{{cite news |last1=Davies |first1=Rob |title=Interserve fights to keep contracts as rivals circle |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/mar/18/interserve-contracts-mitie-serco |accessdate=19 March 2019 |work=Guardian |date=18 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"PA-09Jun2019\">{{cite news |title=Mitie eyeing Interserve amid bid interest in support services arm |url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/news/business/mitie-eyeing-interserve-amid-bid-interest-in-support-services-arm/ |accessdate=10 June 2019 |work=Evening Express |agency=Press Association |date=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, the [[Financial Reporting Council]] launched an investigation into auditor [[Grant Thornton]]'s work on Interserve's financial statements for the years 2015, 2016 and 2017;<ref name=\"Marshall-11Apr2019\">{{cite news |last1=Marshall |first1=Jordan |title=Financial watchdog launches investigation into Interserve auditor |url=https://www.building.co.uk/news/financial-watchdog-launches-investigation-into-interserve-auditor/5098956.article |accessdate=11 April 2019 |work=Building |date=11 April 2019}}</ref> Interserve announced that Mark Whiteling, chief financial officer since September 2017, would be leaving the company;<ref name=\"Kleinman-24Apr2019\">{{cite news |last1=Kleinman |first1=Mark |title=Interserve finance chief quits weeks after rescue deal |url=https://news.sky.com/story/interserve-finance-chief-quits-weeks-after-rescue-deal-11702271 |accessdate=24 April 2019 |work=Sky News |date=24 April 2019}}</ref> and a dispute with [[Sandwell Metropolitan Borough Council|Sandwell MBC]] over allegedly defective Interserve-built school buildings was reported.<ref name=\"Ing-25Apr2019\">{{cite news |last1=Ing |first1=Will |last2=Rogers |first2=Dave |title=Problems with Interserve-built school sees council shell out \u00a31m on emergency classrooms |url=https://www.building.co.uk/news/problems-with-interserve-built-school-sees-council-shell-out-1m-on-emergency-classrooms/5099116.article |accessdate=25 April 2019 |work=Building |date=25 April 2019}}</ref> In June 2019, chairman [[Glyn Barker]] was reported to be preparing to step down,<ref name=\"Kleinman-17Jun2019\">{{cite news |last1=Kleinman |first1=Mark |title=Interserve chairman heads for exit in wake of lender deal |url=https://news.sky.com/story/interserve-chairman-heads-for-exit-in-wake-of-lender-deal-11743401 |accessdate=1 July 2019 |work=Sky News |date=17 June 2019}}</ref> with [[Alan Lovell]] named as his successor in July 2019.<ref name=\"Gross-12Jul2019\">{{cite news |last1=Gross |first1=Anna |title=Interserve appoints turnround specialist Alan Lovell as chairman |url=https://www.ft.com/content/9466c7c2-a46d-11e9-974c-ad1c6ab5efd1 |accessdate=12 July 2019 |work=Financial Times |date=12 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Prior-12Jul2019\">{{cite news |last1=Prior |first1=Grant |title=Interserve appoints Alan Lovell as new chairman |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2019/07/12/interserve-appoints-alan-lovell-as-new-chairman/ |accessdate=15 July 2019 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=12 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Interserve's partner on the Derby EfW project, Renewi, said it was resigned to having its contract terminated, with the plant's handover more than two years late. Renewi said it had a \u00a311.6m claim against Interserve.<ref name=\"Ing-03Jul2019\">{{cite news |last1=Ing |first1=Will |title=Interserve partner on Derby EfW plant puts boot into contractor over delays |url=https://www.building.co.uk/news/interserve-partner-on-derby-efw-plant-puts-boot-into-contractor-over-delays/5100401.article |accessdate=3 July 2019 |work=Building |date=3 July 2019}}</ref> [[Derbyshire County Council|Derbyshire]] and [[Derby City Council]] said they were preparing to cancel the \u00a3950m waste management contract,<ref name=\"Morby-31Jul2019\">{{cite news |last1=Morby |first1=Aaron |title=Derby councils prepare to bin Interserve waste PFI |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2019/07/31/derby-councils-prepare-to-bin-interserve-waste-pfi/ |accessdate=31 July 2019 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=31 July 2019}}</ref> which was formally terminated in early August 2019.<ref name=\"Smulian-05Aug2019\">{{cite news |last1=Smulian |first1=Mark |title=Banks call halt to troubled Derby gasification project |url=https://www.mrw.co.uk/latest/banks-call-halt-to-troubled-derby-gasification-project-05-08-2019/ |accessdate=6 August 2019 |work=Materials Recycling World |date=5 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Interserve announced an operational restructuring of the business; as a result, CEO Debbie White would leave the business, with CFO Mark Morris assuming some of her responsibilities. A City analyst said that the restructuring \"looks like a precursor to the future splitting up the group.\"<ref name=\"Morby-15Nov2019\">{{cite news |last1=Morby |first1=Aaron |title=Interserve restructure paves way for possible break-up |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2019/11/15/interserve-restructure-paves-way-for-possible-break-up/ |accessdate=15 November 2019 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=15 November 2019}}</ref> In March 2020, auditors red-flagged Interserve's finances as the company planned to break up its businesses.<ref name=\"Gill-14Mar2020\">{{cite news |last1=Gill |first1=Oliver |title=Interserve plunged into fresh crisis as finances are red-flagged |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2020/03/14/interserve-plunged-fresh-crisis-finances-red-flagged/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Telegraph |date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n\nInterserve is a support services and construction group,<ref name=ftprofile>[https://www.rns-pdf.londonstockexchange.com/rns/2591R_1-2019-2-27.pdf=IRV:LSE  Interserve RNS] Financial Times Market Data Retrieved 27 February 2019</ref> with its subsidiaries involved in all stages of the life cycle of infrastructure and the [[built environment]].\n\nThe group offers advice, design, construction, equipment and facilities management services for infrastructure. It operates in the [[outsourcing|outsourced]] services and construction markets in the United Kingdom and worldwide.<ref name=ftprofile/>\n\nIt operates in a range of sectors, including [[aviation]], [[central government]], commercial [[offices]], [[defense (military)|defence]], [[education]], [[energy]] and [[water]] [[utilities]], [[health]], [[highway]]s, [[industrial building|industrial]], [[justice]], [[leisure]], [[local government]], [[marine engineering|marine]]/[[river]]s, [[regenerative (design)|regeneration]], [[retail]], [[waste]] and [[welfare to work]] services<ref name=ftprofile/>\n[[File:GC1 1467 COMP.jpg|thumb|283x283px|Interserve provides a range of support services across the transport sector.]]\nThe company's businesses are arranged into the following operating divisions (with principal [[subsidiary|subsidiaries]]) and service provision:\n\n===Professional services===\nInterserve Consulting: [[Program management|Programme management]], [[cost accounting|cost management]] and [[project management]], CDM ([[Construction (Design and Management)]]) co-ordination, [[Health care|healthcare]] planning, sustainability and [[energy management]].<ref name=\"CompaniesHouse\">[http://wck2.companieshouse.gov.uk//wcframe?name=accessCompanyInfo] Companies House WebCHeck</ref>\n\n===Construction services===\nInterserve Construction, Interserve Engineering Services, [[RMD Kwikform]]:  Design and construction for building, mechanical and electrical installation, formwork and falsework, shopfitting and interior fit-out, civil engineering, water treatment and waste.<ref name=CompaniesHouse/>\n\n===Support services===\nInterservefm, Interserve Defence, Interserve Industrial Services, MacLellan International: - Facilities management and business services outsourcing.<ref name=CompaniesHouse/> The company provides facilities in [[private finance initiative]] developments in the [[National Health Service]].\n\n===Investments===\nInterserve Investments: Operates a portfolio of private finance initiative concessions in the UK, primarily in the custodial, defence, education, health and waste sectors.<ref name=CompaniesHouse/> ALso operates a 50%/50% joint venture called Rehab Jobfit within the welfare to work market as a deliverer of the government's Work Programme.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rehabjobfit.com/|title=Rehab Jobfit|accessdate=14 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Financial information==\nFinancial information for the company is as follows:\n<ref>[https://www.interserve.com/docs/default-source/investors/financial-reports/presentation-results/2017/2017-full-year-report.pdf?sfvrsn=3 Interserve 2017 Annual Report] p.122 Interserve. Retrieved 28 February 2019.</ref>\n<ref>[https://www.interserve.com/docs/default-source/investors/financial-reports/presentation-results/2015/2015-annual-report.pdf Interserve 2015 Annual Report] p.98 Interserve. Retrieved 28 February 2019.</ref>\n<ref>[https://www.interserve.com/docs/default-source/investors/financial-reports/presentation-results/2013/2013-full-annual-report.pdf Interserve 2013 Annual Report] p.105 Interserve. Retrieved 28 February 2019.</ref>\n<ref>[http://www.interserve.com/resources/downloads/investors/report-results/2011-ar-full.pdf Interserve 2011 Annual Report] p.65 Interserve. Retrieved 6 March 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.interserve.com/resources/downloads/investors/report-results/2009-ar-full-secure.pdf Interserve 2009 Annual Report] p.64 Interserve. Retrieved 6 March 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.interserve.com/resources/downloads/investors/report-results/2007-ar-full.pdf Interserve 2007 Annual Report] p.58 Interserve. Retrieved 6 March 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.interserve.com/resources/downloads/investors/report-results/2005-ar-full.pdf Interserve 2005 Annual Report] p.52 Interserve. Retrieved 6 March 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.interserve.com/resources/downloads/investors/report-results/2003-ar-full.pdf Interserve 2003 Annual Report] p.46 Interserve. Retrieved 6 March 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.interserve.com/resources/downloads/investors/report-results/2001-ar-full.pdf Interserve 2001 Annual Report] p.32 Interserve. Retrieved 6 March 2013.</ref>\n\n===Annual results===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%; margin:auto;\"\n|\n! [[Revenue]] (\u00a3&nbsp;million)\n! Profit/(loss) before tax (\u00a3m)\n! Net profit/(loss) (\u00a3m)\n! [[Earnings per share]] (p)\n|-\n| 31 Dec 2018\n| 2,697.5\n| (111.3)\n| (128.9)\n| (89.2)\n|-\n| 31 Dec 2017\n| 3,250.8\n| (244.4)\n| (254.4)\n| (176.0)\n|-\n| 31 Dec 2016\n| 3,244.6\n| (94.1)\n| (101.