9\n| label14   = 2005<sup>[a]</sup>\n| data14   = 94.2\n| label15   = 2004<sup>[a]</sup>\n| data15    = 74.7\n| label16   = 2003<sup>[a]</sup>\n| data16    = 72.6\n| label17   = 2002<sup>[a]</sup>\n| data17    = 78.5\n| label18   = 2001<sup>[a]</sup>\n| data18    = 75.5\n| label19   = 2000<sup>[a]</sup>\n| data19    = 68.8\n}}\n\n[a]: Restated to comply with [[IAS 19]], IFRS 3, IAS 10, IAS 39 and IAS12<ref>[http://www.interserve.com/resources/downloads/investors/report-results/2005-ar-full.pdf Interserve 2005 Annual Report] Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements Interserve. Retrieved 4 April 2013.</ref>\n\n==Corporate social responsibility (CSR)==\n\nInterserve was a constituent of the [[FTSE Group|FTSE]]4Good Index,<ref>[http://shares.telegraph.co.uk/news/article.php?id=954403&archive=1&epic=WMH Markets News] The Daily Telegraph Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> designed to objectively measure the performance of companies that meet globally recognised corporate responsibility standards.<ref>[http://www.ftse.com/Indices/FTSE4Good_Index_Series/index.jsp FTSE4Good Index Series] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204155956/http://ftse.com/Indices/FTSE4Good_Index_Series/index.jsp |date=4 February 2012 }} FTSE Website Retrieved 27 March 2013</ref>\n\n=== CSR history===\n\nThe company has since 2002<ref>[http://www.interserve.com/resources/downloads/investors/report-results/2002-ar-full.pdf Interserve 2002 Annual Report] pages 18-22 Interserve. Retrieved 27 March 2013.</ref> published a [[corporate social responsibility]] report section, as a means of [[social accounting]], within its Annual Report and Financial Results.\n\n''[[The Observer]]''\u2019s \"Good Companies Guide\" 2008, compiled to establish Britain's most ethical companies<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/nov/16/observer-good-companies-guide-1 Ethics still matter in hard times] The Observer 16 November 2008 Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> ranked Interserve in its top 20<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/nov/16/observer-good-companies-guide-2 Top of the class] ''The Observer'', 16 November 2008, Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> out of all companies listed on the [[FTSE 350 Index]]\n\nIn 2012 Interserve established the Interserve Employee Foundation, a [[Charitable organisation|registered charity]],<ref>[http://www.charitycommission.gov.uk/Showcharity/RegisterOfCharities/CharityFramework.aspx?RegisteredCharityNumber=1145338&SubsidiaryNumber=0 Register of Charities] Charity Commission website Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> which as noted in the [[British Quality Foundation]] Achievement Award 2012 citation, \"aims to improve the quality of life and life chances for people in the community where they live and operate by utilising the skills, capabilities, resources and enthusiasm of Interserve's employees.\" <ref>[http://www.bqf.org.uk/awards/achievement/2012-winners BQF Achievement Awards \u2013 2012 Winners] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505214617/http://www.bqf.org.uk/awards/achievement/2012-winners |date=5 May 2014 }} British Quality Foundation website Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref>\n\nIt was announced on 25 March 2013<ref name=csr>[http://www.businessgreen.com/bg/interview/2257016/interserve-reveals-how-it-bridged-the-gap-between-sustainability-and-finance Interserve reveals how it bridged the gap between sustainability and finance] Business Green website 25 March 2013 Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref>\nthat Interserve was to establish an [[Integrated reporting]] accounting system, a series of metrics that are designed to measure more than financial performance,<ref>[http://www.theiirc.org/about/ About IR] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130327115801/http://www.theiirc.org/about/ |date=27 March 2013 }} IIRC website Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> by contributing not only towards financial stability, but also sustainable economic development.<ref>[http://www.theiirc.org/ How IR Will Shape The Future of Reporting] IIRC website Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> The company joined the International Integrated Reporting Council worldwide pilot programme, comprising 85 companies,<ref>[http://www.theiirc.org/companies-and-investors/pilot-programme-business-network/ Pilot Programme Business Network] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130312120912/http://www.theiirc.org/companies-and-investors/pilot-programme-business-network/ |date=12 March 2013 }} IIRC website Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> which sought to develop a reporting system that communicates how an organisation's strategy, governance, performance and prospects lead to the creation of value over the short, medium and long term.\nInterserve developed a plan, \u2018SustainAbilities\u2019,<ref>[http://www.businessgreen.com/bg/news/2256133/interserve-pledges-to-halve-carbon-emissions-by-2020 Interserve pledges to halve carbon emissions by 2020] Business Green website 21 March 2013 Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> in conjunction with sustainability adviser, environmentalist and writer [[Tony Juniper]],<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/tonyjuniper Tony Juniper profile] The Guardian Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> co-founder of The Robertsbridge Group,<ref name=csr/> that would measure the company's performance against its knowledge, natural and social capital, in addition to its financial capital.\n\n===Accreditations===\n\nInterserve is accredited with compliance to the following [[International Organization for Standardization]] (ISO) standards:<ref>[http://www.interserve.com/resources/microsites/downloads/sustainability/Sustainability_report_2010.pdf Company Sustainability report 2010] Company website Retrieved 2 April 2013</ref>\n* [[ISO 9000|ISO 9001]] - [[Quality Management]] - deals with the requirements that organisations have to comply with<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iso.org/iso/iso_9000_selection_and_use.htm|title=ISO 9000 selection and use|publisher=International Standards Organisation}}</ref> to meet the fundamentals of quality management systems,<ref name=\"Tsim, Yeung, Leung 2002\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1108/02686900210429669 |title=An adaptation to ISO 9001:2000 for certified organisations |year=2002 |last1=Tsim |first1=Y.C. |last2=Yeung |first2=V.W.S. |last3=Leung |first3=Edgar T.C. |journal=Managerial Auditing Journal |volume=17 |issue=5 |page=245}}</ref> including the eight management principles<ref name=\"Tsim, Yeung, Leung 2002\"/><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/0954412998090 |title=Implementing ISO 9000: A study of its benefits among Australian organizations |year=1999 |last1=Beattie |first1=Ken R. |journal=Total Quality Management |volume=10 |page=95}}</ref> on which the family of standards is based.\n*[[ISO 14000|ISO 14001]] - [[Environmental Management]] - is a standard that sets out the criteria that organisations processes are required to achieve in order to; (a) minimize how their operations (processes etc.) negatively affect the environment (i.e. cause adverse changes to air, water, or land); (b) comply with applicable laws, regulations, and other environmentally oriented requirements, and (c) continually improve in the above.\n* [[OHSAS 18001]] -  [[Occupational Health and Safety]] (OH&S) -  is an international standard for occupational health and  safety [[management system]]s. It specifies the requirements for an organisations OH&S management system that documents through a transparent process its policy and objectives, to take into account legal requirements and information about OH&S risks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bsigroup.com/en/Assessment-and-certification-services/management-systems/Standards-and-Schemes/BSOHSAS-18001/|title=BS OHSAS 18001 Occupational Health and Safety - BSI Group|work=bsigroup.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://opim.wharton.upenn.edu/risk/library/J2007_ESUvol17_PJS.pdf Gamecocks fly safer with OHSAS 18001, QUALITY SYSTEMS UPDATE Volume 17, Number 4, Page 13, 2007<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n\nInterserve have been recipients of the following business and industry awards:\n\n* [[Royal Society for the Prevention of Accidents]] ([[RoSPA]]) \u2013 President's Award <ref name=\"rospa1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2012/presidents-award.aspx|title=President's Award|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n* Interserve Construction 2012,<ref name=\"rospa1\"/> 2011,<ref name=\"rospa2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2011/presidents-award.aspx|title=Winners|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2010/presidents-award.aspx|title=Winners|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n* Interserve Engineering Services 2012,<ref name=\"rospa1\"/> 2011,<ref name=\"rospa2\"/>\n* Interserve Defence 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2009/presidents-award.aspx|title=Winners|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2008/presidents-award.aspx|title=Winners|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2007/presidents-award.aspx|title=Winners|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2006/presidents-award.aspx|title=Winners|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n* Interserve Industrial Services 2005,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2005/presidents-award.aspx|title=Winners|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rospa.com/awards/winners/2004/presidents-award.aspx|title=Winners|work=rospa.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n* British Quality Foundation UK Excellence Award 2012 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bqf.org.uk/awards/ukea/2012-winners|title=UK Excellence Award - 2012 Winners|work=bqf.org.uk|accessdate=22 March 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130423185111/http://www.bqf.org.uk/awards/ukea/2012-winners|archive-date=23 April 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> - Interserve Construction\n* The [[Queen's Award for Enterprise]] 2010<ref>[http://www.birminghampost.net/birmingham-business/birmingham-business-news/business-entrepreneurship/2010/04/30/west-midlands-successes-in-the-queen-s-awards-for-enterprise-65233-26351990/ West Midlands successes in the Queen's Awards for Enterprise] Birmingham Post 30 April 2010</ref> - RMD Kwikform\n* The [[British Safety Council]] \u2013 International Safety Award 2013 \u2013 Distinction \u2013 Interserve Industrial Services Limited<ref>[https://www.britsafe.org/sites/default/files//editor/2013%20ISA%20winners%20list.pdf British Safety Council International Safety Award Winners 2013] British Safety Council website Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref>\n\n==Corporate lobbying==\n\nInterserve has been a member of [[Constructing Excellence]],<ref>[http://www.constructingexcellence.org.uk/membership/memberlist.jsp Constructing Excellence Membership List] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20130423193416/http://www.constructingexcellence.org.uk/membership/memberlist.jsp |date=23 April 2013 }} Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> The [[Business Services Association]]<ref>[http://www.bsa-org.com/about/members The Business Service Association Membership List] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> and [[Build UK]].<ref>[http://builduk.org/members/ Build UK contractor members] Retrieved 1 September 2015</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Accounting irregularities===\n\nOn 14 August 2006 the company announced to the London Stock Exchange that accounting issues relating to the mis-statement of accounting balances within its former Industrial Services Division had been uncovered.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fildes |first=Nic |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/interserve-shares-dive-after-staff-are-suspended-over-fraud-claim-411975.html |title=Interserve shares dive after staff are suspended over fraud claim |publisher=The Independent |date=2006-08-15 |accessdate=2019-03-01}}</ref> The discovery of these accounting irregularities led to a write down in profits by \u00a325.9m, including prior years (see section 3 Financial Information), and six senior managers were suspended with the company stating that accounting mis-statements dating back \"several years\" had been uncovered following changes in the organisation. The ''Daily Telegraph'' reported that 'an investigation had discovered that controls in the division involving work in progress were, in the words of Lord Blackwell, chairman, \"repeatedly evaded over several years in what appears to have been a concerted effort by certain divisional managers to over-state divisional results.\" He added that the board was concerned that the deliberate nature of the evasions had gone undetected for so long despite internal and external audit scrutiny.'<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/2948088/Interserve-finds-accounting-irregularities.html Interserve finds accounting irregularities] The Daily Telegraph 28 September 2006 Retrieved 11 March 2013</ref>\n\n===Office of Fair Trading investigation===\n\nIt was announced that in April 2008 the company became subject to an investigation by the [[Office of Fair Trading]] ([[Office of Fair Trading|OFT]]) under the terms of the Competition Act.<ref>[http://www.oft.gov.uk/news-and-updates/press/2008/52-08#.UTPdGxy4knR OFT issues statement of objections against 112 construction companies] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130311001325/http://oft.gov.uk/news-and-updates/press/2008/52-08#.UTPdGxy4knR |date=11 March 2013 }} Office of Fair Trading Press Release 17 April 2008</ref> The investigation was described by the OFT as \"one of the largest ever Competition Act investigations\" and a total of 112 firms in the construction sector in England were implicated. On 22 September 2009 the OFT concluded that Interserve subsidiary Interserve Project Services Limited had engaged in illegal anti-competitive bid-rigging activities<ref>[http://www.oft.gov.uk/news-and-updates/press/2009/114-09#.UTPd3xy4knT Construction firms fined for illegal bid-rigging] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130310070444/http://oft.gov.uk/news-and-updates/press/2009/114-09#.UTPd3xy4knT |date=10 March 2013 }} Office of Fair Trading Press Release 22 September 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/e1ea26ee-a741-11de-9467-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2MVzHknm5 Builders fined \u00a3130M for rigging bids] Financial Times 22 September 2009</ref> and imposed a fine of \u00a311,634,750.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/business_leaflets/general/parties2.pdf |title=Office of Fair Trading Press Release |access-date=3 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018054827/http://oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/business_leaflets/general/parties2.pdf |archive-date=18 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Alleged blacklisting===\n\nA case was brought by three claimants who were scaffolders and [[Union representative|shop stewards]], against subsidiary company Interserve Industrial Services Limited (IIS) at an [[Employment Tribunal]].<ref name=et1>[http://www.lexology.com/library/detail.aspx?g=9f6d02de-9f63-4805-9447-1057d77ba297 Employer not liable in union blacklisting case] Lexology website 12 December 2012 Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> IIS and the claimants [[trade union]], [[UNITE]], were party to a [[collective agreement]] that provided for the company to \"undertake as far as is practicable to place onto an appropriate contract an NECC accredited senior steward\". A union representative therefore contacted a manager for the company and advocated the employment of the claimants on a contract awarded to IIS. The manager decided on the basis of the contact with the union representative not to recruit any of the three claimants.<ref name=et2>[http://www.employmentcasesupdate.co.uk/site.aspx?i=ed14300 Miller & Ors v Interserve Industrial Services Ltd UKEAT/0244/12/SM] Employment Case Update website Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> The claimants contended that a deliberate decision had been made not to recruit them because of their union activities and that their names had been blacklisted by the company.<ref name=et3>[http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2012/12/11/interserve-beats-blacklist-charge-by-scaffolders/ Interserve beats blacklist charge by scaffolders] Construction Enquirer website Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> The Tribunal ruling supported the IIS evidence that the union tried to bully the company's manager into employing the three men, acted in a combative manner which was resented and that the company did not want to be dictated to about whom to employ.<ref name=et4>[http://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/interserve-cleared-of-blacklisting-allegation Interserve Cleared of blacklisting allegation] The Construction Index website 11 December 2012 Retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> The judgement was subject to an [[Employment Appeal Tribunal]] where the ruling was upheld in Interserve's favour.<ref name=et1/><ref name=et2/><ref name=et3/><ref name=et4/>\n\n===Late payment===\nIn April 2019, Interserve Construction was suspended from the UK Government's [[Prompt payment|Prompt Payment Code]] for failing to pay suppliers on time.<ref name=\"Morby-29Apr2019\">{{cite news |last1=Morby |first1=Aaron |title=Industry giants shamed over late payment |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2019/04/29/industry-giants-shamed-over-late-payment/ |accessdate=29 April 2019 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=29 April 2019}}</ref> It was reinstated in November 2019.<ref name=\"TCI-4Nov2019\">{{cite news |title=Late-paying Kier suspended from Prompt Payment Code |url=https://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/late-paying-kier-suspended-from-prompt-payment-code |accessdate=4 November 2019 |work=The Construction Index |date=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notable construction projects==\n*[[Westminster Bridge]] refurbishment, described by [[Transport for London]] (TFL) as \"revolutionary works to repair the Capital's oldest bridge\"; constructed by Interserve Project Services.<ref>[http://www.tfl.gov.uk/static/corporate/media/newscentre/archive/6246.html Westminster Bridge scoops engineering award] Transport for London website 19 October 2007 Retrieved 11 March 2013</ref>\n*[[Thames Water Desalination Plant]], The first [[water desalination]] plant in the United Kingdom, built in [[Beckton]], east London for [[Thames Water]] by a consortium of Interserve, [[Atkins (company)|Atkins Water]] and Spanish firm [[Acciona]] Agua<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120425235259/http://www.building.co.uk/news/interserve-group-to-build-%C2%A3200m-thames-gateway-water-scheme/3117836.article Interserve group to build \u00a3200m Thames Gateway water scheme] Building Magazine 9 July 2009 Retrieved 2 April 2013</ref>\n\n===Constructed as Tilbury Douglas===\n*[[London Eye]], the Eye is described by its operators as \"the world's tallest [[cantilever]]ed [[observation wheel]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londoneye.com/AboutUs/MerlinEntertainmentGroup/Default.aspx|title=Merlin Entertainments Group|author=Graphico|work=The London Eye|accessdate=22 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329084502/https://www.londoneye.com/AboutUs/MerlinEntertainmentGroup/Default.aspx|archive-date=29 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ingenia.org.uk/ingenia/articles.aspx?Index=77 The Wheel: The British Airways London Eye] Ingenia Issue 6, November 2000, the online journal published by The Royal Academy of Engineering. London</ref><ref>[https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/archive/eye-eye-3-10-06-1999/ Eye Eye] Construction News 10 June 1999 Retrieved 11 March 2013</ref>\n*[[Murrayfield Stadium]], [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]], home of the [[Scottish Rugby Union]] and home venue for [[Scotland national rugby union team|the Scottish National Rugby team]], as well as hosting games in the [[1991 Rugby World Cup|1991]], [[1999 Rugby World Cup|1999]] and [[2007 Rugby World Cup]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/archive/18feb93-uk-tilbury-scores-try-20m-stadium-redevelopment-cntract-18-02-1993/|title=18Feb93 UK: TILBURY SCORES TRY - \u00a320M STADIUM REDEVELOPMENT CONTRACT.|work=https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n*[[The Den]], [[Bermondsey]], southeast London home of English [[Association Football|football]] club [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/archive/25mar93-uk-lions-new-den-millwall-fc-25-03-1993/|title=25Mar93 UK: LIONS' NEW DEN - MILLWALL FC.|work=https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Rothera Research Station]], [[Adelaide Island]], [[British Antarctic Territory]] for [[British Antarctic Survey]].<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Jxq-t-yLFmcC&pg=PT147&lpg=PT147&dq=tilbury+douglas+construction+contracts|title=A Summer in Antarctica |year=2011 |author1=  Jones, J.J. |accessdate=11 March 2013 |isbn=978-1467880077 |publisher=Author House |location = UK}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=mO6gV1BUB7MC&pg=PT104&lpg=PT104&dq=british+antarctic+survey+tilbury+douglas|title= Terra Incognita: Travels in Antarctica |year=2010 |author1=  Wheeler, Sara. |accessdate=11 March 2013 |isbn=978-1407051826 |publisher=Random House |location =London, UK}}</ref><ref>[https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/archive/01apr93-antarctica-builders-feel-chill-of-rising-costs-research-station-01-04-1993/ Antarctica: Builders Feel Chill of Rising Costs \u2013 Research Station] Construction News 1 April 1993 Retrieved 11 March 2013</ref>\n\n===Constructed by RM Douglas===\n*[[International Convention Centre, Birmingham]], constructed in joint venture with Turner International.<ref name=\"thefreelibrary.com\">[http://www.thefreelibrary.com/High+regard+for+council+in+skyline+awards.-a069962270 High Regard for council in skyline awards] The Birmingham Post 3 February 2001 Retrieved 11 March 2013</ref><ref>[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/0100news/0100localnews/tm_objectid=15130532&method=full&siteid=50002&headline=man-who-helped-build-new-brum-name_page.html Man who helped build new Brum] The Birmingham Post 29 January 2005 Retrieved 11 March 2013</ref>\n*[[Symphony Hall, Birmingham]], home of the [[City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra]] (part of the International Convention Centre project).\n*[[National Exhibition Centre]], Birmingham, UK.<ref name=\"thefreelibrary.com\"/><ref>[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/0100news/0100localnews/tm_objectid=15130532&method=full&siteid=50002&headline=man-who-helped-build-new-brum-name_page.html Man who helped build new Brum] The Birmingham Post 3 February 2001 Retrieved 29 January 2005</ref>\n*[[Don Valley Stadium]], [[Sheffield]], [[England]], venue for the 1991 [[Universiade|World Student Games]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.supertram.com/donvalley.html|title=Stagecoach Supertram: The Don Valley|work=supertram.com|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Controlled-access highway|Motorways]] including:\n** [[M1 motorway|M1]]<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m1/m1-crick-to-barlborough-j18-to-j30/index.cfm The Motorway Archive] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> - Jct 18 to 30 (Kirby Muxloe \u2013 Whetstone) and Jct 18 to 30 (Nuthall \u2013 Sandiacre)\n** [[M4 motorway|M4]]<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m4/m4-wales/m4-in-wales-contract-details.cfm The Motorway Archive] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> - East of Jct37(A48) to Jct39 (Pyle by-pass) and J44 to J46 (Morriston by-pass)<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m4/m4-wales/m4-in-wales-lon-las-to-llangyfelach-j44-to-j46. The Motorway Archive] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041233/http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m4/m4-wales/m4-in-wales-lon-las-to-llangyfelach-j44-to-j46. |date=4 March 2016 }} Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref>\n** [[M40 motorway|M40]]<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m40/m40-waterstock-j8a-to-umberslade-m42--j3a/index.cfm The Motorway Archive] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> - Jct13 to Jct15 (Warwick South) and Jct12 to Jct13 (Gaydon)\n** [[M42 motorway|M42]]<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m42-birmingham-to-nottingham-motorway-M5-j4a-to-tamworth-j11/lickey-end-j1-to-alvechurch-j2.cfm The Motorway Archive] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> - Jct1 to Jct2 (Lickey End to Alvechurch) and Jct4 to Jct8 (Solihull Section)<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m42-birmingham-to-nottingham-motorway-m5-j4a-to-tamworth-j11/solihull-section-j4-to-j8 The Motorway Archive] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> \n** [[M50 motorway (Great Britain)|M50]]<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m50-the-ross-spur-motorway--ross-bypass/index.cfm The Motorway Archive] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref>\n** [[M54 motorway|M54]]<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m54-the-telford-motorway/index.cfm The Motorway Archive] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> - Jct1 to Jct3 (Donington section)\n** [[M6 motorway|M6]]<ref name=m6>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m5/m5-j1-to-j3-and-m6-j13-to-j1-midland-links-motorways/index. The Motorway Archive] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304043724/http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m5/m5-j1-to-j3-and-m6-j13-to-j1-midland-links-motorways/index. |date=4 March 2016 }} Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> - Jct7 to Jct8 (Rayhall to Great Barr), North of Jct6 to Jct7 (Great Barr to Perry Bar) and advance river works for [[Gravelly Hill Interchange]] colloquially known as [[Spaghetti Junction]]\n** [[A38(M)]]<ref>[http://www.ukmotorwayarchive.org/midlands.htm The Motorway Archive] Retrieved 7 March 2013</ref> - Tower Road to Inner Ring Road (Lancaster Circus).\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Lightering|Lighterage]] \n* [[Facilities management]]\n* [[Dredging]]\n* [[Dunkirk evacuation]]\n* [[Confederation of British Industry]]\n* [[RMD Kwikform]]\n* [[Office of Fair Trading]]\n* [[Integrated reporting]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.interserve.com/default.asp Official site]\n* [http://uk.finance.yahoo.com/q/pr?s=IRV.L Yahoo profile]\n* [http://markets.ft.com/Research/Markets/Tearsheets/Summary?s=IRV:LSE FT.com tearsheet]\n\n{{Construction industry in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Construction and civil engineering companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Business services companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the London Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Construction and civil engineering companies established in 1884]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Reading, Berkshire]]\n[[Category:Private providers of NHS services]]\n[[Category:Business services companies established in 1884]]\n[[Category:1884 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSailing barge(link changed toThames sailing barge) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interserve"}
{"title_page": "Kermit E. Krantz", "text_new": "{{short description|American physician}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Kermit E. Krantz\n| image         = Dr Kermit E Krantz.jpg\n| alt           = Image of Kermit E. Krantz\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Kermit Edward Krantz\n| birth_date    =   {{Birth date|1923|06|04}}\n| birth_place   = [[Oak Park, Illinois]], [[United States|US]]\n| death_date    =  {{Death date and age|2007|07|30|1923|06|04}} \n| death_place   = [[Prairie Village, Kansas]], US\n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = \n| alma_mater =  [[Northwestern University]]\n| occupation    = Obstetrician and gynecologist\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| spouse = Doris Cole (c. 1945\u20132007; his death)\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Kermit Edward Krantz''' (June 4, 1923 \u2013 July 30, 2007)<ref name=obit>{{cite news|title=Obituaries \u2013 Kermit E. Krantz |url=http://www.legacy.com/KansasCity/DeathNotices.asp?Page=LifeStory&PersonID=91819956 |work=[[The Kansas City Star]] |date=1 August 2007 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201324/http://www.legacy.com/KansasCity/DeathNotices.asp?Page=LifeStory&PersonID=91819956 |archivedate=27 September 2007 }}</ref> was a surgeon, inventor and faculty member at the [[University of Kansas Medical Center]].  He is most known as the co-developer of the [[Marshall-Marchetti-Krantz]] [[Marshall-Marchetti-Krantz|(MMK)]], a medical procedure for [[stress urinary incontinence]] which he performed over 5000 times. He served as Chairman of Obstetrics and Gynecology at the [[University of Kansas]].\n\nHe was largely credited with desegregating the [[maternity ward]] of that hospital in the 1960s.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |work=Center Express |url=http://www2.kumc.edu/publications/centerexpress/080207.pdf00 |title=In Memoriam |date=August 2007 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKrantz, an identical twin and the youngest of eight children, was born June 4, 1923, in [[Oak Park, Illinois]].  He worked his way through school college and medical school performing research, curating a museum for [[Northwestern University]] anatomy professor Leslie Arey) and selling newspapers, as he had lost both of his parents by the age of 13.\n\nHe was married to Doris Cole (1920\u20132014) for 62 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obituary: Doris Cole Krantz|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/kansascity/obituary.aspx?pid=170181907|work=[[Kansas City Star]]|date=16 March 2014|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170303101804/http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/kansascity/obituary.aspx?pid=170181907|archivedate=3 March 2017|via=[[Legacy.com]]}}</ref>\n\nKrantz died on July 30, 2007 in [[Kansas City, Kansas]] from the complications of a stroke.\n\n==Academics and work history ==\n*Dr. Krantz graduated from [[Northwestern University]] with a Bachelor of Science (1945), a Master of Science in Anatomy (1947), and a Medical Doctorate (1948.)\n*He served his residency at both the [[Cornell Medical College]] (NYC) at New York Lying-In Hospital (now [[New York-Presbyterian Hospital]]) and at the [[University of Vermont]]\n*Held the position of Assistant Professor at the University of Vermont\n*Held the position of Assistant Professor at the [[University of Arkansas]]\n*Held the position of (Full) Professor of Anatomy and Professor of Obstetrics and Gynecology\n*He served as Chairman of Obstetrics and Gynecology at the University of Kansas for 31 years.<ref>http://www2.kumc.edu/publications/centerexpress/080207.pdf</ref>\n*1990 he was honored as the first University Distinguished Professor at the University of Kansas School of Medicine.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n*Associate to the Executive Vice-Chancellor for Facilities Development\n*Dean for Clinical Affairs (Chief of Staff) at KUMC (1972\u20131974)\n*Over 75 books, journals or book contributions were credited to Dr. Krantz, along with nine medical educational/instructional movies.\n\n==Awards, honors, and service==\n*Endowed Chair at the University of Kansas; Kermit E. Krantz Professor and Chair of Obstetrics and Gynecology <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www2.kumc.edu/aa/fa/pdf/ListAllProfship.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-01-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710174732/http://www2.kumc.edu/aa/fa/pdf/ListAllProfship.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*Markel Scholar in Medical Science (1957)\n*Bowens-Brooks Fellow \u2013 New York Academy of Medicine\n*Literary (honorary) Doctorate from [[William Woods University]]\n*Foundation Prize, 1950, American Gynecological and Obstetrical Society<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agosonline.org/history/foundation-prizes.asp |title=American Gynecological and Obstetrical Society |publisher=Agosonline.org |date= |accessdate=2013-01-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317084911/http://www.agosonline.org/history/foundation-prizes.asp |archive-date=2012-03-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*Distinguished Service Award from the American College of Obstetrics and Gynecologists\n*Won the [[American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists]]' \"Robert A. Ross Award\" 12 times (from 1972\u20131983, more than any other) for his work with the Navy\n*The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists award the \"Kermit E Krantz Award\" for service in the Armed Forces' Air Force Section, in honor of Dr. Krantz since 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acog.org/About_ACOG/ACOG_Sections/Air_Force_Section |title=Air Force Section |publisher=ACOG |date=2012-10-07 |accessdate=2013-01-21}}</ref>\n*In 1985, he received the [[Department of the Army Outstanding Civilian Service Award]], one of the highest civilian awards the US Army/Pentagon can bestow.\n*Won the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists' \"Col. Edward Zimmermann Award\" in 1981 for his work with the Army\n*University of Kansas Honorary Medical Alumnus Award, 1994\n*Listed on the Hall of Fame at [[Oak Park and River Forest High School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprfhs.org/information_for/Development/Tradition_Of_Excellence/Saved/TRADITIONOFEXCELLENCE2old.html |title=OPRF |publisher=Oprfhs.org |date=2012-11-30 |accessdate=2013-01-21}}</ref>\n*Executive Committee of the National Association of Planned Parenthood Physicians\n*President of the Society of Medical Consultants of the Armed Forces<ref>http://www.smcaf.org/SMCAFpastofficers.pdf</ref>\n*Chief civilian consultant to the Surgeon General\n*Chairman for the Committee on Gynecological Practice/American College of Obstetrics and Gynecologists\n*Association of Professors of Gynecology and Obstetrics/Wyeth Career Achievement Award<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.apgo.org/binary/WYETH06.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-01-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315041320/https://www.apgo.org/binary/WYETH06.pdf |archive-date=2016-03-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.apgo.org/foundation/index.cfm/cat/foundation%20awards/objid/0003C091-A765-1B1B-820A9EEF40F4B4F2.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://archive.is/20060926122834/http://www.apgo.org/foundation/index.cfm/cat/foundation%20awards/objid/0003C091-A765-1B1B-820A9EEF40F4B4F2.htm |date=September 26, 2006 }}</ref> (1988)\n*Examiner for the American Board of Gynecologists\n*Scientific Advisory Board for the Armed Forces Institute of Pathology (1984\u20131992)\n* In 2004, Northwestern University honored Dr. Krantz by dedicating the Arey/Krantz Museum of Anatomy at the [[Feinberg School of Medicine]].<ref>\n[https://www.northwestern.edu/magazine//summer2008/classnotes/inmemoriam.html In Memoriam]. ''Northwestern Magazine'', Summer 2008</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060902010508/http://www.feinberg.northwestern.edu/ar2005/content/education/did_you_know.html discover : education], Feinberg.northwestern.edu (via archive.org)</ref>\n*32nd Degree Mason\n*President of the International Family Planning Research Associates\n\n==Innovations==\nBeyond the MMK, Krantz held four patents,<ref>[http://patft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect1=PTO2&Sect2=HITOFF&p=1&u=%2Fnetahtml%2FPTO%2Fsearch-bool.html&r=0&f=S&l=50&TERM1=krantz%2C+kermit+e&FIELD1=INNM&co1=AND&TERM2=&FIELD2=&d=PTXT Patent Database Search Results: IN/\"krantz, kermit e\" in US Patent Collection<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> including:\n\n* Expansible [[tampon]]\n* Surgical closure device and method\n* Surgical [[stent]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{Commons category|Kermit E. Krantz}}\n* [http://www.kumc.edu/  University of Kansas Medical Center & KU School of Medicine]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120220162920/http://www.feinberg.northwestern.edu/ar2005/content/education/did_you_know.html Northwestern University, Feinberg School of Medicine Annual report]\n* [http://patft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect1=PTO2&Sect2=HITOFF&p=1&u=%2Fnetahtml%2FPTO%2Fsearch-bool.html&r=0&f=S&l=50&TERM1=krantz%2C+kermit+e&FIELD1=INNM&co1=AND&TERM2=&FIELD2=&d=PTXT US Patent and Trademark Office]\n* [http://www.legacy.com/KansasCity/DeathNotices.asp?Page=LifeStory&PersonID=91819956 Kansas City Star Obituaries Page]\n* [http://www.acog.org/ American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Krantz, Kermit E}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:American gynecologists]]\n[[Category:American obstetricians]]\n[[Category:American urologists]]\n[[Category:Cornell University staff]]\n[[Category:Feinberg School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Arkansas faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Kansas faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Vermont faculty]]\n[[Category:Identical twins]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American physician}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Kermit E. Krantz\n| image         = Dr Kermit E Krantz.jpg\n| alt           = Image of Kermit E. Krantz\n| caption       = \n