yn\u00e4s IF|Brynas IF]] (J20 SuperElit)\n|}\n\n==Farm teams==\n* [[Binghamton Senators]] ([[American Hockey League]])\n* [[Elmira Jackals]] ([[ECHL]])\n\nThe Senators continued their affiliation with the [[Binghamton Senators]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) and added an affiliation agreement with the [[Elmira Jackals]] of the [[ECHL]].<ref name=\"elmira-bulletin\">{{cite web |publisher=Ottawa Senators |url=http://senators.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=379713 |title=Bulletin: Senators Reach Affiliation Agreement with Elmira |date=August 14, 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-14| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080817210110/http://senators.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=379713| archivedate= 17 August 2008 | url-status= dead}}</ref> In previous years, Elmira had accepted players from Binghamton on a player-by-player basis. The new agreement formalized the arrangement of Elmira as the primary affiliate of Binghamton and the secondary affiliate of Ottawa.<ref name=\"elmira-bulletin\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2008\u201309 NHL season]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Ottawa Senators}}\n{{Ottawa Senators seasons}}\n{{2008\u201309 NHL season by team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2008-09 Ottawa Senators Season}}\n[[Category:Ottawa Senators seasons]]\n[[Category:2008\u201309 NHL season by team|Ottawa Senators season, 2008-09]]\n[[Category:2008\u201309 in Canadian ice hockey by team|Ottawa]]\n", "text_old": "{{NHLTeamSeason\n|League=NHL\n|Season=2008\u201309\n|year=2008\n|Team=Ottawa Senators\n|Conference= [[Eastern Conference (NHL)|Eastern]]\n|ConferenceRank=11th\n|Division= [[Northeast Division (NHL)|Northeast]]\n|DivisionRank=4th\n|Record= 36\u201335\u201311\n|HomeRecord= 22\u201312\u20137<ref name=\"sweden\">Includes one game in Sweden.</ref>\n|RoadRecord= 14\u201323\u20134<ref name=\"sweden\"/>\n|GoalsFor= 217\n|GoalsAgainst= 237\n|GeneralManager= [[Bryan Murray (ice hockey)|Bryan Murray]]\n|Coach= [[Craig Hartsburg]] <small>(Oct.\u2013Feb.)</small> <br> [[Cory Clouston]] <small>(Feb.\u2013Apr.)</small>\n|Captain= [[Daniel Alfredsson]]\n|AltCaptain= [[Dany Heatley]]<br />[[Chris Phillips]]\n|Arena=[[Scotiabank Place]]\n|Attendance= 19,081 (99.6%)\n|GoalsLeader= [[Dany Heatley]] (39)\n|AssistsLeader= Daniel Alfredsson (50)\n|PointsLeader= Daniel Alfredsson (74)\n|PlusMinusLeader= Daniel Alfredsson (+7)\n|PIMLeader= [[Chris Neil]] (146)\n|WinsLeader= [[Alex Auld]], [[Brian Elliott]] (16)\n|GAALeader= Alex Auld (2.47)\n}}\n\nThe '''2008\u201309 Ottawa Senators season''' was the team's [[Ottawa Senators seasons|17th season]] in the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL). The team began the season with a new head coach, [[Craig Hartsburg]], and numerous personnel changes after narrowly making the [[2008 Stanley Cup playoffs]]. However, the team had a losing record under the new coach and he was fired in February, replaced by [[Binghamton Senators]]' head coach [[Cory Clouston]]. The team improved its record under Clouston, but not enough to qualify for the [[2009 Stanley Cup playoffs|2009 playoffs]], ending an 11-year string of qualifying for the playoffs.\n\n{{TOClimit|limit=2}}\n\n==Off-season==\nIt was an off-season of numerous personnel changes. [[Wade Redden]], a long-time Senator, signed a contract as a free agent with the [[New York Rangers]]. [[Ray Emery]] and [[Brian McGrattan]], considered poor influences in the dressing room, were discarded. The Senators re-signed forwards [[Shean Donovan]], [[Chris Kelly (ice hockey)|Chris Kelly]] and [[Antoine Vermette]] and made several free agent signings, including [[Alex Auld]], [[Jarkko Ruutu]] and [[Jason Smith (ice hockey)|Jason Smith]]. After an extended period of negotiations with [[Andrej Mesz\u00e1ro\u0161|Andrej Meszaros]] failed to produce a contract, the [[Tampa Bay Lightning]] showed interest in the defenceman, who was a restricted free agent. Unable to provide the draft picks needed to compensate the Senators, a trade was made and the Senators received [[Filip Kuba]], [[Alexandre R. Picard|Alexandre Picard]] and a first-round pick in the [[2009 NHL Entry Draft]] from Tampa Bay.\n\n===Highlights===\nOn June 5, it was reported that [[Wade Redden]] would not sign a contract paying $3.5&nbsp;million annually with the Senators. He instead became an unrestricted free agent (UFA) on July 1 and signed a six-year, $39&nbsp;million contract with the [[New York Rangers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/NHL/Ottawa/2008/06/06/5792821-sun.html |accessdate=2008-06-09 |title=Redden to go on market |last=Garrioch |first=Bruce |publisher=Slam! Sports |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120715155914/http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/NHL/Ottawa/2008/06/06/5792821-sun.html |archivedate=2012-07-15 |url-status=live }}</ref> On June 13, 2008, the Senators named [[Craig Hartsburg]], coach of the [[Ontario Hockey League]]'s [[Sault Ste. Marie Greyhounds]], the new head coach after having interviewed candidates [[Bob Hartley]] and [[Peter DeBoer]]. Hartsburg signed a three-year contract with the Senators.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=240543&lid=headline&lpos=topStory_main |title=HARTSBURG INTRODUCED AS NEW HEAD COACH IN OTTAWA |date=2008-06-13 |accessdate=2008-06-13 |publisher=TSN.ca |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090112173005/http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=240543&lid=headline&lpos=topStory_main |archivedate=2009-01-12 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn June 20, the day of the [[2008 NHL Entry Draft]], the Senators placed [[Ray Emery]] on waivers and re-signed [[Chris Kelly (ice hockey)|Chris Kelly]] to a new four-year, $8.5&nbsp;million contract.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://senators.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=366569 |title=Kelly Staying with Senators |date=2008-06-20 |accessdate=2008-06-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007214841/http://senators.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=366569 |archivedate=2008-10-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> At the draft, the Senators selected [[Erik Karlsson]] with their first-round pick (15th overall) and proceeded to select [[Patrick Wiercioch]] (42nd overall), [[Zack Smith (ice hockey)|Zack Smith]] (79th overall), [[Andr\u00e9 Petersson|Andre Petersson]] (109th overall), [[Derek Grant (ice hockey, born 1990)|Derek Grant]] (119th overall), [[Mark Borowiecki]] (139th overall) and [[Emil Sandin]] (199th overall).\n\nOn July 1, the Senators announced that they had signed goaltender [[Alex Auld]] to a two-year contract worth $1&nbsp;million annually. Auld is expected to serve as a backup to [[Martin Gerber]] for the 2008\u201309 season. On July 2, the Senators announced that they had re-signed forward [[Shean Donovan]] to a two-year contract at $625,000 per season. The Sens also announced that they have signed forward [[Jarkko Ruutu]] to a three-year contract worth $1.3 million per season. On July 5, the Ottawa Senators announced that [[Antoine Vermette]] had elected to take the club to salary arbitration. The Senators and Vermette agreed to a two-year deal on July 31. On July 8, the Senators announced that they had signed defenceman [[Jason Smith (ice hockey)|Jason Smith]] to a two-year, $5.2&nbsp;million contract.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=242839&lid=sublink09&lpos=headlines_nhl |title=Senators sign free agent defenceman Smith |date=2008-07-08 |accessdate=2008-07-09 |publisher=TSN.ca}}</ref> On July 16, the Senators announced that they will host the [[Detroit Red Wings]] in their official home-opener on October 11. On July 17, the Ottawa Senators and CHUM Radio announced that the club and The Team 1200 had signed a multi-year extension to their agreement to broadcast Senators' games. The original ten-year contract expired at the end of the 2007\u201308 season. On July 31, the Ottawa Senators and Antoine Vermette avoided going to arbitration by agreeing to terms on a new two-year contract worth $5.525&nbsp;million. Vermette would make $2.525&nbsp;million and $3&nbsp;million for the 2008\u201309 and 2009\u201310 seasons respectively.\n\nOn August 29, in a trade similar to the [[Alexei Yashin]] trade in 2001, former first-round pick [[Andrej Mesz\u00e1ro\u0161|Andrej Meszaros]] was traded to the [[Tampa Bay Lightning]] in exchange for [[Filip Kuba]], [[Alexandre R. Picard|Alexandre Picard]] and a first-round pick in the [[2009 NHL Entry Draft]] (obtained by Tampa Bay in an earlier trade with the [[San Jose Sharks]]).<ref name=\"slam-mes\">{{cite web |url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/NHL/Ottawa/2008/08/31/6623611-sun.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130115094031/http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/NHL/Ottawa/2008/08/31/6623611-sun.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-15 |title=Mes Wanted to Stay |publisher=Slam Sports |accessdate=2008-09-05}} </ref> Meszaros was a restricted free agent demanding $1&nbsp;million more per season than what the Senators were willing to offer. After Tampa threatened to offer Meszaros an offer sheet with picks as compensation on August 28, the Senators opted to make a trade with Tampa.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/NHL/Ottawa/2008/08/29/6606541-sun.html |title=Bolting to Sunshine State? |accessdate=2008-09-05 |publisher=Slam Sports}}</ref> Meszaros subsequently signed a six-year, $24&nbsp;million contract on August 30 with the Lightning.<ref name=\"slam-mes\"/> On September 2, the Senators made a deal with the [[Vancouver Canucks]] and traded defenceman [[Lawrence Nycholat]] for centre/right winger [[Ryan Shannon]]. On the same day, they signed another former Canucks player, [[Brad Isbister]], who was an unrestricted free agent. On September 27, veteran defenseman [[Luke Richardson]] re-signed on a one-year, two-way contract with the Senators for his second season with the club.\n\n==Pre-season==\nOn October 2, the Senators played their first-ever game in Europe, a pre-season exhibition game in [[Gothenburg]], Sweden, against [[Fr\u00f6lunda HC|Frolunda HC]],<ref name=\"nhl-note\"/> which Ottawa captain [[Daniel Alfredsson]] played for before joining the NHL and during the [[2004\u201305 NHL lockout]]. \n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Time\n! Opponent\n! Location\n! Score\n|-\n| September 20\n| 7:00pm\n| [[New York Rangers]]\n| Scotiabank Place\n| W, 3\u20132\n|-\n| September 22\n| 7:00pm\n| [[New York Rangers]]\n| Madison Square Garden\n| L, 2\u20131\n|-\n| September 24\n| 7:00pm\n| [[Philadelphia Flyers]]\n| Scotiabank Place\n| W, 3\u20131\n|-\n| September 26\n| 7:30pm\n| [[Montreal Canadiens]]\n| Bell Centre\n| L, 5\u20130\n|-\n| September 27\n| 7:00pm\n| [[Montreal Canadiens]]\n| Scotiabank Place\n| W, 3\u20131\n|-\n| October 2\n| 1:00pm\n| [[Fr\u00f6lunda HC]]\n| Scandinavium Arena\n| W, 4\u20131\n|}\n\nThe Senators finished the 2008 pre-season with a record of 4\u20132\u20130\u20130.\n\n==Regular season==\nThe Senators started their season with a pair of games in [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]]. The Senators played the [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] twice at the [[Scandinavium]] on October 4 and October 5.<ref name=\"nhl-note\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nhl.com/nhl/app?articleid=351323&page=NewsPage&service=page |title=Four NHL teams to open the 2008\u201309 regular season in Europe Oct. 4\u20135 |publisher=NHL.com |date=January 26, 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-24}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The teams split the results, with the Penguins winning the first in overtime and the Senators winning the second. New Senator defenceman [[Filip Kuba]] picked up at least one point in each of the Senators' first eight games of the season, setting the NHL record for consecutive team games with assists from the start of a season by a defenceman. The previous mark of seven was set by [[Brad Park]] with the [[Boston Bruins]] in [[1981\u201382 Boston Bruins season|1981\u201382]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=394558 |title=NHL.com - News |date=November 26, 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-26}}</ref> All points were assists and Kuba did not score his first goal with the Senators until November 13.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://senators.nhl.com/team/app?gameNumber=229&gameType=2&page=Recap&season=20082009&service=page |date=November 14, 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-18 |title=Ottawa Senators Recap| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081219094700/http://senators.nhl.com/team/app?gameNumber=229&gameType=2&page=Recap&season=20082009&service=page| archivedate= 19 December 2008 | url-status= dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Alexander Nikulin (ice hockey)|Alexander Nikulin]], who had been demoted to the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL)'s [[Binghamton Senators]], threatened to return to [[Russia]] unless he was traded. As a result, he was traded from Binghamton to the [[Arizona Coyotes|Phoenix Coyotes]]' AHL affiliate, the [[San Antonio Rampage]], for [[Drew Fata]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://coyotes.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=390320 |title=Coyotes acquire Nikulin from Senators |publisher=coyotes.nhl.com |date=2008-11-03 |accessdate=2008-11-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726183437/http://coyotes.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=390320 |archivedate=2011-07-26 }}</ref>\n\nFor a game on November 22 against the [[New York Rangers]], the Senators unveiled their new third jersey. Marketed as \"Back in Black,\" the jersey is primarily black. The Senators' primary logo moves to the shoulders and the nickname \"SENS\" is across the front of the jersey.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://senators.nhl.com/index.html |title=Back in Black |accessdate=2008-11-18| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081103193458/http://senators.nhl.com/index.html| archivedate= 3 November 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nPrior to that game, the Senators players, the team below the playoff cutoff in the standings for most of October through November, decided to grow [[moustache]]s, similar to the [[playoff beard]] tradition of teams in the playoffs. The team started growing the moustaches following a loss to the [[Montreal Canadiens]] on November 20. The idea originated with [[Dany Heatley]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/story/2008/11/21/rangers-senators-preview.html |publisher=CBC Sports |date=November 22, 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-18 |title=Win-starved Senators adopt moustache look}}</ref>\n\nOn November 27, the Senators waived [[Luke Richardson]], a veteran of nearly 20 years in the NHL. He was not picked up by any other team and subsequently retired. He had not seen much playing time with Senators, and had been a healthy scratch several times in the season.\n\nFrom December until early January, the Senators took an eight-game road trip as Scotiabank Place was used for the [[2009 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships]]. The team, already well back of a playoff spot, received intense scrutiny by the media, believing a \"shake-up\" of some kind was imminent. The team only won one game on the road trip, and on January 7, Owner Eugene Melnyk was compelled to respond to media reports of the imminent firings of General Manager [[Bryan Murray (ice hockey)|Bryan Murray]] and Head Coach [[Craig Hartsburg]]:\n<blockquote>\n&ldquo;Contrary to what is being reported today by the media, I have made no decisions with respect to any personnel changes within the Senators organization. Winning remains our No. 1 priority and there is a collective focus by our management, our coaching staff and our players to deliver this to our fans.\n<br/>\nI, along with our fans, will do nothing but continue to remain fully committed to our Senators and enthusiastically cheer them on to a successful second half of the season.\n<br/>\nThis is crunch time. Now, more than ever, is the time to rally behind our team. We don\u2019t surrender half-way though the season.\n<br/>\nEvery victory from here on in matters. We know it and the fans know it. Period.&rdquo;\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://senators.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=402756 |title=Bulletin: A statement from Ottawa Senators owner Eugene Melnyk |publisher=Ottawa Senators |date=January 8, 2009 |accessdate=2009-01-09| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090109080810/http://senators.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=402756| archivedate= 9 January 2009 | url-status= dead}}</ref></blockquote>\nAt the end of the road trip on January 8, the club was 13 points behind the eighth and final playoff spot, held by the [[Buffalo Sabres]]. The ''Ottawa Citizen'' launched the \"[[John Tavares (ice hockey)|Tavares]] Cup,\" similar in spirit to the \"[[Alexandre Daigle|Daigle]] Cup\" of 1993, to keep track of the bottom five teams in the NHL, all of which had a chance, at least via the draft lottery, to draft the highly rated junior player, John Tavares. At the time of the start of the \"competition,\" the Senators were within the lowest five teams in the League.<ref>{{cite news |work=Ottawa Citizen |date=January 7, 2009 |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/Sports/Nothing+decided+Melnyk+says/1153969/story.html |title=Nothing decided, Melnyk says, but ... |last=Warren |first=Ken |accessdate=4 February 2009 <!--DASHBot--> }}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nAlso on January 7, forward [[Jarkko Ruutu]] received a suspension of two games for biting in an altercation with a [[Buffalo Sabres]] forward on January 6. It was Ruutu's second suspension of the season, after elbowing a [[Montreal Canadiens]] forward earlier in the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/sports/story.html?id=1151963|work=Ottawa Citizen |date=January 7, 2009 |title=Ruutu suspended for two games|accessdate=2009-01-09}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nOn January 9, 2009, goaltender [[Brian Elliott]] was recalled by Ottawa from Binghamton.<ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/story/2009/01/10/senators-rangers.html | work=CBC News | title=Senators hope Elliott supplies boost | date=January 10, 2009| accessdate= 4 February 2009 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> He had been named the AHL's Goaltender of the Month for December.<ref name=\"OttawaCitizen\">https://ottawacitizen.com/Sports/Elliott+save/1162577/story.html{{dead link|date=September 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On January 15, Senators goaltender [[Martin Gerber]] was demoted to Binghamton for a two-week conditioning stint; he was placed on waivers and was assigned to Binghamton on January 27.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://senators.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=406460 |publisher=Ottawa Senators |date=January 27, 2009 |accessdate=2009-01-28 |title=Bulletin: Senators assign Gerber to Binghamton |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090131024906/http://senators.nhl.com/team/app?articleid=406460&page=NewsPage&service=page |archive-date=2009-01-31 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Elliott started six games in a row and remained with Ottawa.\n\nOn January 29, less than a month after previous comments to the media about the Senators, Eugene Melnyk responded to media speculation about possible organization changes with another memorable quote:\n\n<blockquote>&ldquo;Anybody that says we should blow up this organization should get their own bomb and go blow themselves up.&rdquo;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/NHL/Ottawa/2009/01/29/8188036-sun.html |title=Sens owner Melnyk misfires |date=January 30, 2009 |accessdate=2009-01-30 |publisher=Canoe - Slam! Sports |last=Brennan |first=Don}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAt the time, the Senators remained near the bottom of the League in 29th place, with the lowest goal-scoring record in the NHL.\n\nHowever, only three days later, on February 2, Head Coach Craig Hartsburg was fired, ending his tenure with the Senators at only 48 games. Following a 7\u20134 loss to the [[Washington Capitals]] on February 1, Hartsburg had called out his team for not playing hard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=265548&lid=headline&lpos=topStory_nhl|publisher = TSN|date = February 2, 2009|accessdate = 2009-02-02|title =Struggling Senators Fire Coach Hartsburg| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090205072429/http://tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=265548&lid=headline&lpos=topStory_nhl| archivedate= 5 February 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Binghamton Senators' Head Coach [[Cory Clouston]] was elevated to head coach of Ottawa for the balance of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20090202.wsptsens0202/GSStory/GlobeSports/?page=rss&id=RTGAM.20090202.wsptsens0202 |title=Senators fire Hartsburg |date=February 2, 2009 |accessdate=2009-02-02 |publisher=globesports.com}}</ref> Clouston became the fourth head coach to coach the Senators in a year, prompting the media to dub the players as \"coach-killers.\"<ref>{{cite web|publisher=National Post |date=February 3, 2009 |accessdate=2009-02-03 |title=Players downplay coach-killer label |url=https://nationalpost.com/sports/story.html?id=1247896 |last=Warren |first=Ken}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Assistant Coach Curtis Hunt was also let go (he became the Binghamton head coach) and recently-retired defenceman Luke Richardson joined the coaching staff as an assistant.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/NHL/Ottawa/2009/02/04/8260701-sun.html |work=Slam! Sports |title=Sens Notebook |last=Garrioch |first=Bruce |date=February 4, 2009 |accessdate=2009-02-04}}</ref>\n\nOn February 12, former Head Coach [[John Paddock]] (who had moved on to coach the AHL' [[Philadelphia Phantoms]]) weighed in on the firing, stating that at some point that GM Bryan Murray would be held accountable:\n<blockquote>&ldquo;I think now he's next in line. We were 14 games over .500 when I was fired. They're seven under now. Somebody needs to take responsibility for that. Whether the coaches he hired and fired were good or not, they're his players and they're either not playing good or can't play, one or the other.&rdquo; He was then asked which was the case: &ldquo;The players are not very good, that's the problem.&rdquo;<ref>{{cite news |work=Camden Courier-Post |date=February 12, 2009 |accessdate=2009-02-12 |title=Parent tries to stay on top unit |url=http://www.courierpostonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2009902120377 |last=Gormley |first=Chuck}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nPaddock apologized to Murray via e-mail. Murray commented, \"I'm disappointed and a little bit surprised by it. I'm not sure what purpose he was trying to achieve doing that. He sent me an apology. The only complaint I ever had with John was that I didn't think he worked hard enough at getting himself ready and getting the team ready to play games.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Flyers suffer ugly defeat |date=February 13, 2008 |accessdate=2009-02-13 |work=Camden Courier-Post |last=Gormley |first=Chuck |url=http://www.courierpostonline.com/article/20090213/SPORTS04/902130354/1006/NEWS01}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nLate in February and early in March, as the season neared the trade deadline, the team still held out hold of making the playoffs although the team remained over ten points out of a playoff spot, as the team was winning more often with Clouston. The Senators began making roster deals, sending [[Dean McAmmond]] and a 2009 first-round pick for [[Chris Campoli]] and [[Mike Comrie]]. By the [[NHL trade deadline]] day of March 4, Murray admitted to the media that the club would be \"sellers\" and had given up hope of making the playoffs. On March 4, [[Antoine Vermette]] was traded to the [[Columbus Blue Jackets]] for goaltender [[Pascal Leclaire]] and a draft pick. Martin Gerber was put on waivers three times and was finally picked up by the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]].\n\nAlthough the club improved its record under new coach Clouston, including a 10\u20135\u20130 record in March, it was not enough to salvage the season. On March 31, following a loss to the [[Florida Panthers]] and a win by the Montreal Canadiens, the club was officially eliminated from playoff contention for the first time since 1996.\n\nAlthough eliminated, the team continued to play well, including a nine-game win streak on home ice. By April 8, the team's record under Clouston was 19\u201310\u20133 and he was rewarded with a two-year deal to continue coaching the Senators.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://senators.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=417229 |title=Sens keeping Clouston behind bench |date=April 8, 2009 |accessdate=2009-04-08 |publisher=Ottawa Senators. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100109235045/http://senators.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page |archive-date=2010-01-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Divisional standings===\n{{2008\u201309 NHL Northeast Division standings|team=OTT}}\n\n===Conference standings===\n{{2008\u201309 NHL Eastern Conference standings|team=OTT}}\n\n==Schedule and results==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" width=90% style=\"clear:both; margin:1.5em auto; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background:#FF0000; color:#FFD700\" | 2008\u201309 Game log\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|<div class=\"NavFrame\">\n<div class=\"NavHead\" style=\"background:black; \"><span style=\"color:white;\">October:  4\u20135\u20131 (Home: 1\u20134\u20131; Road: 3\u20131\u20130)</span></div>\n<div class=\"NavHead\" style=\"background:black; color:#CBA135\">October</div>\n<div class=\"NavContent\" style=\"text-align:center; display:none;\">\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! width=\"5%\"  | Game\n! width=\"5%\"  | R\n! width=\"8%\" | Date\n! width=\"8%\"  | Score\n! width=\"12%\" | Opponent\n! width=\"5%\" | Attendance\n! width=\"5%\"  | Recap\n! width=\"8%\"  | Record\n! width=\"3